<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>CPAC:  Highlights of CPAC '95</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center>
<H3> CONSERVATIVE POLITICAL ACTION CONFERENCE<BR>1995</H3>
<HR SIZE = 3><BR>

<IMG SRC="/cpac/cpac1.gif">
<IMG SRC="/cpac/cpac2.gif">
<IMG SRC="/cpac/cpac3.gif"><BR><BR>
<HR SIZE = 3><BR>
</center>
In 1973, a handful of Americans met in Washington D.C. to affirm their support for Conservative ideals.  That first small gathering has blossomed into the Conservative Political Action Conference (CPAC), the largest annual gathering of conservative activists in America.
<P>
CPAC is designed to advance important everyday issues such as taxes, crime, culture and foreign policy and to provide basic conservative viewpoints and solutions.
<P>
Past speakers include President Ronald Reagan, President George Bush, Lamar Alexander, Dick Armey, Pat Buchanan, Bill Bennett, Dick Cheney, Bob Dole, Newt  Gingrich, Phil Gramm, Jesse Helms, Jack Kemp, Jeane Kirkpatrick, G. Gorden Liddy, Trent Lott, Oliver North, P.J. O'Rourke, Dan Quayle, Pat Robertson, and Phyllis Schlafly, to name a few.
<P>
CPAC, a three day event, February 22nd, 23rd and 24th, 1996, will take place at the Omni Shoreham Hotel in Washington, D.C.  The conference is composed of speeches, forums and panel discussions from recognized leaders.   It is sponsored by the American Conservative Union, in cooperation with the journals Human Events and <I> National Review </I>and co-sponsored by over 60 nationally known organizations.
<p><center>[ <a href="/cpac">CPAC '96 Home</a> | <a href="/cpac/agenda.html">Agenda</a>
 ]</center>
<P>
<HR SIZE = 3><BR>
<IMG SRC="/cpac/cpac4.gif" ALIGN=LEFT>
<IMG SRC="/cpac/cpac5.gif"ALIGN=RIGHT> <BR><P><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR>
<HR SIZE = 3><BR><BR>
<CENTER><H3> Highlights of CPAC '95</H3></CENTER>
<P>
From Newt Gingrich to Bob Dole to Phil Gramm to Patrick Buchanan and everyone in between, they all came to CPAC '95.
<P>
Some of the highlights included the first major speech given by former Vice President Dan Quayle following his decision not to run for President in 1996; a debate between Robert Novak and Sam Donaldson on the relevancy of the media; an analysis by House Majority Leader Newt Gingrich on the  Contract With America; a speech by Senator Phil Gramm on the balanced budget; a preview of the 2nd and 3rd 100 Days by Patrick Buchanan; as well as speeches by Jeane Kirkpatrick, Lamar Alexander, Congressman Istook, Governor John Engler, Bill Bennett, Jack Kemp and many more.
<P>
The Presidential Banquet topped off the Conference with Ashbrook Award recipient, Malcolm Wallop, special guest Dick Armey and a keynote address by Bob Dole.
<P>
The Awards Banquet hosted Dave Thomas of Wendy's, Football Hall of Fame star Frank Gifford, and a special address by G. Gordon Liddy.
<P>
The activity did not end in the conference hall, the Exhibit Hall provided CPAC registrants the opportunity to discuss the latest social and economic issues with our 60-plus Co-Sponsors; to obtain the most current conservative books, brochures and newsletters; and to purchase the latest and greatest political memorabilia.
<P>
<center>
[ <a href="/cpac/">CPAC '96 Home</a> | <a href="/conservative/join.html.cgi">Join ACU</a> | <a href="/cpac/97.html">CPAC '97</a> ]
</center>

</BODY>
</HTML>
