<html><head>
<title>
A Letter from Congressman Christopher Cox
 -- ACU</title>
</head>
<body>
From: Congressman Christopher Cox<p>


<p>
Dear Taxpayer:
<P>
Think back to last April 15, when you finally finished with another year's labor at the command of the IRS. Think about the scores of receipts, the paperwork nightmare, the headaches.
<P>
If you're like most Americans, you've probably fantasized more than once about life without the IRS.
<P>
But did the thought ever occur to you that you might live to see the end of the IRS? Could this actually happen?
<P>
Since last year, things have changed drastically in Washington. Ideas that weren't even on the table for the 40 years of Democrat control of Congress are suddenly achievable goals in our bold new agenda.
<P>
The most dramatic proposal of all is to abolish the IRS.
<P>
This is not an idle dream. It is a serious and sound reform, and I'm inviting you to join me in making it happen.
<P>
The liberal media are not reporting it, but already most of the Republican Congressional leadership favors either abolishing the IRS entirely or radically reforming it and reducing its power, its reach, its control over individual Americans.
<P>
These Republican leaders include Speaker Newt Gingrich, House Majority Leader Dick Armey, House Ways and Means Chairman Bill Archer, Senate Majority Whip Trent Lott, Senator Dick Lugar, Senator Phil Gramm, and many others.
<P>
We have to be realistic about such a bold vision. It will be extremely difficult for Congress to muster the courage to actually vote to abolish the IRS until the members receive a clear signal from the American people.
<P>
That is why I need you to take a few minutes and do two things to help change our tax laws and reduce the size and intrusiveness of government:
<P><UL>
<LI>First, sign the enclosed petition to Congress.
<P>
<LI>Second, send a contribution of at least $10 or $15 to us immediately, and consider sending $25, $50 or $100 to help the American Conservative Union (ACU) fund this campaign to abolish the IRS.
</ul><P>
<p>
Our campaign cannot get off the ground without your support.
<P>
The House Ways and Means Committee recently held hearings that revealed some astonishing facts. We learned that the costs of complying with current income tax laws has ballooned to over $200 billion each and every year. We also learned that it takes over 14,700 pages of regulations and another 200,000 pages of interpretations of these regulatlons to explain our tax code.
<P>
It's no wonder that over half of America's taxpayers are now forced to hire accountants and lawyers to prepare their tax returns!
<P>
Think how much time, income and worry you would personally save if you didn't have to spend hundreds of hours or more during the coming year to be a bookkeeper for the government. Think of how much personal freedom and independence you would gain if the govermnent no longer forced you to record every detail of your flnancial life. Think of all the late evenings and weekends you could spend with your family, your friends, your work, and your community if they were no longer devoted to figuring out how much of your hard-earned money you have to send to the IRS!
<P>
Have you ever wondered how freedom-loving Americans surrendered so much liberty to the bureaucrats in Washington, D.C.? In fact, it happened so gradually; we didn't object loudly enough, or in time. But the truth is, American life has changed dramatically--and for the worse--since the income tax started to take control of personal budgets and fueled the growth of the welfare state.
<P>
When I was growing up, in the 1950s, government did not consume the 40% of our gross domestic product (GDP) that it does today. In 1954, government consumed 20% of GDP. As a result, the average fanlily, making the average national income, paid income tax at the rate of two percent. Social Security taxes were juct one and one-half percent of wages.
<P>
I know, because my father earned just about the national "average" back then. Our family, like most others, could afford a 3 bedroom house, even though only one spouse worked. Mortgage rates averaged just 4 percent. Despite spending much more on national defense in the 1950s to defend against communism, the federal budget was balanced. In this low tax environment, people enjoyed steady gains in their standard of living.
<P>
That kind of freedom and opportunity can once again become a part of American life. But it will happen only if we are willing to reduce the size of government--and only if we recognize that the income tax in America has proven to be a miserable failure.
<P>
Do we have the vision to seize this opportunity?
<P>
As I said earlier, there is strong aupport in the new Congress to abolish the IRS. But Congress rarely acts before voters push them. Pollticians need to hear the persistent and insistent voice of the American people.
<P>
The American people, in turn, want a clear vision of a better life, in which individual opportunity and responsibility replace the failed welfare state. They want a government responsive to their concerns instead of those of bureaucrats. Abolishing the IRS is the central act that embodies that vision.
<P>
I can assure you personally that, for the first time in many years, Congress is really listening to the American people. I wouldn't have been able to write this letter a year ago, because I knew then that Congress wouldn't even think about abolishing the IRS and simplifying our tax system. For forty years, Congress had a vested interest in getting more of your money to fund pet projects of questionable value. But the world has changed.
<P>
The 1994 elections came as a wake up call even to my Democratic colleagues. As a result, congress is listening as never before, because people have joined together and are speaking out in a strong, united voice for many issues: reduced government regulation of individuals and businesses, 
 protection of private property, lower taxes and smaller government.
<P>
There are many groups organized at the local, state and national levels to fight for these issues. But there isn't the necessary organization to lead millions of taxpayers at both the local and national levels in the massive campaign needed to abolish the IRS and end the most noxious and offensive government excess of all.
<P>
That is why I've agreed to help the American Conservative Union give voice to the growing public demand for a simple, fairer tax system without the IRS.
<P>
There are already several proposals before the Congress that will move us toward our goal, including Majority Leader Dick Armey's proposal to replace the current income tax with a flat tax. With your help one of these significant income tax reform plans will pass. And every one of these reforms will help reduce the intrusion of the IRS into our daily lives.
<P>
Whatever path we choose, the ultimate objective must be to accomplish our vision of abolishing the IRS. For that to become a reality, we must begin working immediately. The day after last November's election, my good friend Bill Archer, the new Chairman of the powerful Ways and Means Committee, shocked the Washington establishment by declaring that his number one goal is the total abolition of the income tax.
<P>
Chairman Archer is convinced that, to make this possible, we must get two-thirds of the congress to vote for a Constitutional Amendment to repeal the 16th Amendment, which established our current system of
income taxes. And then we must work to get three-fourths of the state legislatures to agree.
<P>
Once that happens, the income tax will no longer be a part of the U. S. Constitutlon, and the IRS wlll lose its reason for existence.
<P>
When we accomplish our goal of eliminating the IRS, we will have done more to accomplish the objectives of limited government than we ever imagined was possible.
<P>
I believe this historic effort cannot succeed without the leadership of the ACU.
<P>
For over 30 years the ACU has been America's largest and most effective grass roots organization working to lower taxes and greatly reduce the scope of government.
<P>
ACU was in the front ranks in l993 and 1994 with TV advertisements, direct mail, town hall meetings, press conferences, and other methods to organize and lead coalitions to stop the Clintons' socialized health plan.
<P>
But, I can assure you, that battle was nothing like the war it will take to abolish the IRS.
<P>
ACU Chairman David Keene tells me that a successful campaign will take about two years and a budget of at least $25,000,000 to repeal the 16th Amendment, abolish the IRS, and replace today's income tax with a tax that is smaller, simpler, and fairer.
<P>
Those of us in the Congressional leadership are working to build support for income tax repeal right now, but I have to tell you that our best chance will probably come after the next presidential and Congressional elections... If ACU starts our national crusade immediately!
<P>
Speaker Newt Gingrich is fond of saying that organizing a large number of people to solve a problem is a four-step process:
<P>
First, Establish the Vision. Our vision is an America of opportunity, liberty and personal responsibility, without the 
IRS and without the counterproductive income tax.
<p>
Second, Identify Your Goal. Our goal is the repeal of the 16th Amendment by 1997, and the ratification of repeal by the states by the end of l999.
<p>
Third, Define Your Strategy. our strategy is to raise $25,000,000 and use it to reach 100,000,000 taxpayers with our message. That message will encourage them, in turn, to urge their Congress and state legislators to support repeal of the 16th Amendment.
<P>
Fourth, Develop Appropriate Tactics. Our tactics are as follows:
<P>
<ul>
<LI> Establish ABOLISH THE IRS COMMITTEES around the country to coordinate grass roots activity.
<P>
<LI> Circulate petitions and obtain 20,000,000 signatures to abolish the IRS. 
<P>
<LI> Generate 45,000,000 letters and phone calls to members of Congress with our message.
<P>
<LI> Supply talk show hosts and other media outlets with information about the abuses regularly committed by the IRS.
<P>
<LI> Publish a special monthly newsletter for our activists and supporters.
<P>
<LI> Work toward getting both the Republican and Democratic parties to adopt a plank calling for repeal of the 16th Amendment as part of their 1996 electoral platforms.
<P>
<LI> Give every candidate running for President, Congress and state office in 1996 information on the need to abolish the IRS and repeal the 16th amendment.
<P>
</ul>
But ACU can't move forward with this program until you assure me of your support.
<P>
If you and others I am writing today do their part and send what they can afford, whether $15, $25, $50, $100 or more, ACU will be able to start this massive grass roots effort immediately.
<P>
It is also vital that YOU sign the enclosed petition.
<P>
After receiving your signed petition, ACU will advise your elected representatives in the U. S. Congress of your support for our mission.
<P>
We all understand how expensive this type of campaign is in today 's world. ACU will simply not be able to start this campaign and distribute our petitions unless we receive your financial support.
<P>
Our income tax system wastes hundreds of billions of your dollars each year that the government doesn't even receive in taxes. Government agents force us to work hundreds of hours a year keeping records, filling out complicated and unreadable forms, and answering harassing questions. We spend too much time and too such money in learning how to prevent the lRS from claiming money we've earned that isn't legally theirs.
<P>
Then, even after we have done all of this, we are forced to live in fear that the IRS will penalize us, or demand that we gather up years of our financial records for their inspection. If the IRS can find some mlnor error, they penalize us even further.
<P>
Is this any way for America to treat its citizens?
<P>
There is a better way for people to llve together in a free society. We have the vislon to take us toward this better path. He can live without the IRS and without the 16th Amendment.
<P>
So, please take a few minutes right now and return your signed petition and a generous contribution to help launch a massive, grass-roots lobbying campaign to abolish the IRS and replace it with a smaller, simpler, and fairer tax system.
<P>
Sincerely,
<P>

Christopher Cox
<P>
Chairman<br>
House Republican Policy Committee<br>
<P>

P. S. Your signed petition will help 
convince Members of Congress to repeal the 16th Amendment, to abolish the IRS and its more than 14,000 pages of complicated and outrageous rules and regulations, and to dismiss the 115,000 IRS employees that cause Americans to live in fear of their own government.
<P>
In order for this to happen, ACU needs you to send a contribution today of at least $15. If at all possible, please send as much as you feel it would be <u>worth to you</u> to abolish the IRS. Send $25, $50, or $100 If you can only afford $10 or $15, that will be extremely helpful and allow ACU to spring into action with their battle plan to repeal the 16th Amendment by 1997.
<p>
[ <a href="donate-u.html">Sign</a> the Petition and Contribute to the Repeal the 16th Amendment Campaign.]<P>

[ <a href="/conservative/welcome.html">ACU Home</a> | <a href="/conservative/join.html.cgi">Join ACU</a> ]
<P>

</body>
</html>
