<HEAD>
<TITLE>ABIC - Finger Pointing Page - 9/23/96</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#ffffff">
<a href="/abic/top.map"><img src="/abic/images/top.gif" border="0" ALT="Americans Bac
k in Charge" ISMAP></a><p>
<P>
<P>
<center>
<FONT SIZE=4>Finger Pointing Page</FONT><br>
<i>(This week we point our fingers at a group of good guys...)</i><P>
<p>
<HR>
<P>
<H3>"The Mysterious Disappearance of the Metcalf Amendment:<BR>
<EM>A True Life Congressional Thriller</EM>. . .</H3>
<P>
<b>Chapter 3</b>
<P>
The Metcalf Amendment Reappears...<br>
....as the Thompson Amendment!!
</center><p>
In Chapters 1 and 2, we learned that ABIC has been following the disappearance of the so-called Metcalf Amendment. In July, we pointed the finger at the 67 House members who voted against the Amendment offered by Rep. Jack Metcalf (R - WA) to stop the automatic pay increase scheduled for members of Congress.  The House adopted the amendment and under its provisions, Congress would receive no payraise this year.  (Note:  Congressional salaries in 1996 are $133,644 per year.)
<P>
We also learned that when the bill came out of the Senate committee, the Metcalf amendment had <b><i>vanished without a trace</i></b>.  No one knew how it disappeared or whodunnit! In <a href="/abic/ptf/7-29-96.html.cgi">Chapter 1</a>, ABIC pointed the finger at the prime suspects.
<P>
While no amount of detective work will reveal how the Metcalf Amendment disappeared in the Committee, <b>the day was ultimately saved by none other than...<P>
<center><h3>Senator Fred Thompson (R-TN)!</b></h3></center>
<P>
<center>
<table BORDER=0 ROWS=3 COLUMNS=3 CELLSPACING=5 CELLPADDING=20>
<tr>
<td ALIGN="right" VALIGN="middle"><img src="/abic/images/rt.gif"></td>
<td ALIGN="center"><img src="/abic/images/thompson.gif"><br>
Fred Thompson<br>
R-Tennessee<br>
Chairman</td>
<td ALIGN="left" VALIGN="middle"><img src="/abic/images/l.gif"></td>
</tr>
</table>
</center>
<P>
<DD><b>Sen. Thompson,</b> joined by <b>Sen. Jesse Helms</b> (R-NC), <b>Sen. Strom Thurmond</b> (R-SC), <b>Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison</b> (R-TX), <b>Sen. Paul Wellstone</b> (D-MN), and <b>Sen. Charles Grassley</b> (R-IA), <b>sponsored an amendment on the floor of the Senate which would do the exact same thing as the Metcalf Amendment.</b> It would stop the automatic congressional payraise!  The measure passed the Senate with a voice vote.<p>
<p>
<center>
<table BORDER=0 ROWS=3 COLUMNS=3 CELLSPACING=5 CELLPADDING=20>
<tr ALIGN=center>
<td><img src="/abic/images/helms.gif" ALIGN="bottom"><br>
<center>Jesse Helms<br>
R-North Carolina</center></td>
<td></td>
<td><img src="/abic/images/thurmond.gif" ALIGN="bottom"><br>
<center>Strom Thurmond<br>
R-South Carolina</center></td>
</tr>
<tr ALIGN=center>
<td><img src="/abic/images/hutchiso.gif" ALIGN="bottom"><br>
<center>Kay Bailey Hutchison<br>
R-Texas</center></td>
<td VALIGN=top><img src="/abic/images/fin.gif"></td>
<td><img src="/abic/images/grassley.gif" ALIGN="bottom"><br>
<center>Charles Grassley<br>
R-Iowa</td></center>
<tr ALIGN=center>
<td></td>
<td><img src="/abic/images/wellston.gif" ALIGN="bottom"><BR>
<center>Paul Wellstone<br>
D-Minnesota</center></td>
</center>
</table>
<P>
In his floor statement, Sen. Thompson said, "The amendment we offer today is based upon the simple proposition that while we are asking the American people to make these (sacrifices), we must ask the same of ourselves...  We need to lead by example by showing the American people that we in Congress are willing to make a personal contribution to the effort of balancing the budget."
<P>
So, this week ABIC points the finger at a group of <i><b>good</i></b> guys: the six co-sponsors of the Thompson Amendment.
<P>
<p>
