<html>
<head>
<title>ABIC - Cleta Mitchell's Senate Testimony</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<a href="/abic/top.map"><img src="/abic/images/top.gif" border="0" ALT="Americans Back in Charge Foundation" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<center>
<h3>Testimony of Cleta Deatherage Mitchell</h3>
<h4>Director and General Counsel<br> 
Term Limits Legal Institute, a project of Americans Back In Charge Foundation
<p>
Subcommittee on the Constitution, Federalism and Property Rights<br>
U.S. Senate
<p>
January 25, 1995</h4>
</center>
<p>
 	My name is Cleta Mitchell.  I am the Director and General Counsel of the Term Limits Legal Institute in Washington, D.C.  The Term Limits Legal Institute was established in 1991 as a project of Americans Back in Charge, the first national term limits organization devoted to helping grassroots citizens committees in the various states follow the example of Colorado in 1990, limiting the terms of members of Congress by state action.  The Term Limits Legal Institute was created to defend the right of citizens to vote on term limits proposals and then to defend those enactments in the courts once passed by the voters.  We all are aware of the litigious nature of our society.  This is true as well in the political arena.  Since 1990, the term limits movement has been confronted with over 30 different lawsuits challenging the right of voters even to have the opportunity to consider the issue of term limits and then seeking a "second opinion" from the courts after the voters' verdict in favor of term limits was delivered in state after state or city after city.
<p>
	I am pleased to be in this forum today, because I believe that it is in the political arena--not in the courts--where the decision about term limits for members of Congress should be decided.
<p>
	There has been much discussion today about the public policy reasons for limiting congressional terms, and I won't reiterate those here.
<p>
	I want to focus briefly, however, on three primary points.
<p>
	First, I believe that when we begin amending the Constitution it is necessary to be thoughtful, careful and deeply respectful of the principles on which the entire framework of our government was founded.  I do not take lightly the notion of amending the Constitution, and I would not be here advocating amending it if I didn't believe that the principle at stake here was one that the Founding Fathers believed in but didn't bother to write down.  There has been ample testimony today about the history of the principle of rotation and the way in which term limits fit into the Constitutional framework.  It is my opinion that had Thomas Jefferson not been in France during the Constitutional Convention, we would not be here arguing this point today because he would have insisted on a mandatory rotation being written into the Constitution.  His concerns about the abandonment of the mandatory rotation were met with the response that the principle of rotation was imbedded in the national psyche and would be carried out "voluntarily".  Jefferson believed that voluntary rotation would, over time, erode and that is exactly what happened.
<p>
	But Jefferson <i>was</i> in France and it now settles upon our shoulders to complete a task that wasn't concluded in Philadelphia in 1787.  It is our role to write into the Constitution a principle that was inherent in the design of the institution of Congress--but which has eroded to the point of nonexistence: the principle of rotation and citizen responsibility for self-government.   
<p>
	In other words, the principle of term limits is a principle on which the national government was founded and one on which our notions of self-government are grounded.  The health of our democracy is at stake unless we restore this principle to our Constitution.   
<p>
	Second, any term limitation should treat the House and the Senate equally.  As we all recall from our history and civics classes, the first great hurdle at the Constitutional Convention was the tension between the small and the large states.  "The Great Compromise" that created the bi-cameral Congress with both a House and a Senate, based on separate forms of representation to accommodate the concerns and anxieties of BOTH small and large states, was the central underpinning of the constitutional convention.  Absent that compromise and the agreement to establish a Congress with 2 houses--equal in stature and authority, but differently designed--there would have been no constitution.   
<p>
	I do not believe that it is our task here to tamper with that design.  We are not here today and we should not be in the business of tinkering with the relative strength of the House vs. the Senate.  That is why I am here today urging you to adopt a term limits bill that treats the House and Senate equally under term limits: with 12 year limits on service in either House of Congress.  I believe that such an approach allows us to address the problems and the issues related to term limits without doing damage to the relative balance of power between the House and the Senate or the Great Compromise of the Philadelphia convention.   
<p>
	Further, it is the principle of term limits for members of Congress that is important.  There is a very real political consideration insofar as promoting a term limits measure that has some hope of success.  What that means, in my opinion, is that the Senate should not be promoting a bill that is dead on arrival in the House.  I served 8 years in the Oklahoma legislature as a member of the House of Representatives.  It is my considered opinion that there is not a House of Representatives anywhere on the planet that will pass a measure that allows Senators to serve in office twice as long as they can.  I believe that we should be focusing our energy on the principle of term limits and garnering support for a measure that can be successfully achieved--rather than wasting time fighting over something that is neither desirable nor attainable, namely, the 6 year term limit for House members.   
<p>
	Third, those who argue that the "people" are demanding a six year term limit for House members are, in my opinion, incorrect.  I know of no opinion poll that has asked the American people to state whether they would be supportive of a 12 year term limit if that's all the Congress was willing to pass.  If the choice is between a 12 year limit for House members and NO limit for either the House or Senate, I daresay that the people would choose 12 year term limits for all members of Congress.  That is a perfectly reasonable approach and it is one that, I believe, is achievable, which, again is part of the task before you.   
<p>
	The experience in the states is not as one-sided in favor of 6 year limits for House members as some might have you believe.   
<p>
	In the only state that has voted on both 6 year and 12 year limits on the members of the House of Representatives, Colorado, the 12 year limit received 153,000 more votes than did the 6 year limit.  While I realize that in the past few years there have been polls indicating that people were so angry at Congress that they would probably have supported a term limit of 6 months, I also believe that when the American voter steps into the polling booth, a sense of great responsibility sets in--and the evidence from Colorado is, I think, compelling.   
<p>
	Further, the reason that 6 year term limits for House members have been enacted in most states has not been a grassroots decision, but a requirement for receiving funds from the national term limits group that is dedicated to 6 year term limits.  It was important in the early days of this movement to bring the debate on term limits from the notion of 18 or 24 year term limits, which certain national figures who professed a commitment to term limits were actually promoting.  I believed in those days that it would be useful to promote the 6 year term limit for the purpose of insuring that the outer limits of discussion would ultimately be set at 12 year limits.  That goal has been achieved because no one is discussing anything today beyond a twelve year limit.  Today, however, we must move beyond  political rhetoric and name-calling and get about the business of seriously considering the public policy issues related to term limits and how the goals we espouse can best be achieved.
<p>
  	We must do everything in our power to see that the 104th Congress sends to the States a constitutional amendment to limit congressional terms.  That is what we are here today to discuss and I hope it is what this Congress is serious about doing.   
<p>
	President Clinton spoke over the weekend about the problems of the American people having become political "couch potatoes".  I find that objectionable for two reasons.  First, the American people have gotten up from their couches and spoken very loudly and firmly about their desire for term limits for members of  Congress.  To ignore our voices is to say "Go back to your couch.  We want you to become involved, but only if you agree with those of us who do this political stuff full time."  The second problem I have with the "political couch potato theory" is that those of you who lead our government can't have it both ways:  you can't tell us, the people, that we don't know enough to govern ourselves, that you have to be an "expert" to be involved in politics and government, and then wonder why normal everyday people throw up their hands and drop out of the process.  I believe that supporting term limits is essential to a revitalizing of our national democratic health and affirming our commitment to self-government.
<p>
	In  closing, I believe that we must approach this task with a love of the Congress and a careful concern for its design that was understood by our Founding Fathers.  That is why George Will entitled his book supporting term limits Restoration.   I join Mr. Will in his belief that by limiting the terms of members of Congress, we will be able to restore to Congress its rightful place of honor in our national life and in the hearts and minds of the American people.   	
<p>
	I urge your swift consideration and passage of the amendment to the Constitution to establish 12 year term limits for members of the United States House and Senate.   
<p>
	Thank you.
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<center>
<a href="/abic/ftb/">Footing the Bill</a> - <a href="/abic/ptf/">Pointing the Finger</a> - <a href="/abic/sbg/welcome.html.cgi">Spotlight on Big Government</a><br>
<a href="/abic/new.html.cgi">What's New?</a> - <a href="/abic/about.html.cgi">About ABIC</a> - <a href="/abic/features.html.cgi">Features</a> - <a href="/abic/links.html.cgi">Links</a> - <a href="/abic/listserv.html.cgi">ListServ</a><br>
<a href="/townhall/">Town Hall</a> - <a href="mailto:abic@abic.org">E-Mail ABIC</a>
</center>

<p align=center>
