<html><head>
<title>Setting Limits -- ABIC</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<a href="/abic/top.map">
<img src="/abic/images/top.gif" 
ALT="Americans Back in Charge Foundation" border="0" ISMAP></a><p>
Book by Cleta Mitchell, Director, ABICF<br>
<img align="left" src="images/book.gif">
<center><h3>Setting Limits:<br>
The Truth About Why Congress Defeated <br>
the Term Limits and Balanced Budget Amendments in 1995</h3></center>
<hr width="55% size="3">
<p>     
As America looks toward the end of an incredible twentieth century and the
beginning of both a new millenium and a new century, we are well served to think
about the kind of government we want as we move into this new era.

<p>
Most of us believe that it is time for new answers to the problems and
challenges we face as a country:  an aging population, staggering deficits, and a
government in Washington that seems unable to cope with the major issues of the
day.
<p>
<table><tr><td width="60%">
That is why overwhelming majorities of the American people favor
enactment of two constitutional amendments:  one to permanently limit the tenure
of members of the U.S. Congress and the other to permanently require a balanced
federal budget.
<p>
In the 104th Congress that convened in January, 1995 and will adjourn at the
end of this year, we have made progress toward the twin goals of the balanced
budget amendment and term limits -- but we haven't achieved the necessary 2/3
vote in both houses of Congress for final passage of either.
</td>
<td><h3>Chapters Include:</h3>
<ul>
<li><b><a href="/abic/wethepeople.html.cgi">We the People</a><br>
<li><a href="/abic/antagon.html.cgi">The Antagonists</a><br>
<li><a href="/abic/unrep.html.cgi"><i>The Un-Representatives</i></a><br>
<li><a href="/abic/welfare.html.cgi">The Congressional Welfare Kings & Queens</a><br>
<li>The Good Old Boys<br>
<li><a href="/abic/decoys.html.cgi">Hatfield and the Decoys</a><br>
<li>Good Guys/ Bad Guys<br>
<li>Opportunity Knocks</b><br></ul>
</center></td></tr></table>

<p>
We have much work to do in order to secure congressional passage of these
constitutional amendments.  Our Founding Fathers intended that it would be
somewhat difficult to amend the constitution -- but it shouldn't be impossible, and
it isn't.
<p>
The active participation in the political process by average, patriotic citizens
is what it will take to see both of these amendments through passage by the
Congress and ratification by the necessary 38 state legislatures.
<p>
We can -- and we must -- reclaim our government from the governing elite
in Washington, D.C. and return it to the oversight and control of the American
people in our  home towns and our states.
<p>
That is what the balanced budget and term limits amendments will help
accomplish -- and we must keep up the effort for both until we see these
amendments added to our constitution.
<p><br>
<p align="right"
<a href="/abic/cdmbio.html.cgi"><b>Cleta Mitchell</b></a><b>, Chairman<br>
Americans Back In Charge Foundation</b>
</p>
