<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Organizational Trends -- CRC</TITLE>

</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/crc/images/bg.gif">
<a href="/crc/images/sidebar.map"><img src="/crc/images/sidebar.gif" alt="Navigation Bar"
 border="0" align="left" ISMAP></a>
<blockquote>
<center>
<img src="/crc/images/hdr-ot.gif">
</center>
<p>
<i>March, 1996</i>
<P>
<h2>The &quot;Children's Initiative&quot;:</h2>
<P>
<I><B>How the Classroom Became a Vehicle<br>
for Universal Health Coverage<BR>
</i></b>
<P>
<I><FONT COLOR=#000000>by Genevieve M. Young<BR>
</FONT></I><p>

<a href="#Children">The Children's Initiative:  It Takes A Child To Disguise A Policy</a>
<br><a href="#Policy">Education Policy</a>
<br><a href="#Brave">Kentucky's Brave New World</a>
<br><a href="#Medicaid">The Medicaid Program in Pennsylvania:  Out Of Control</a>
<br><a href="#Robert Wood">Robert Wood  Johnson Foundation: &quot;Leveraging&quot;
 Governmemt funding</a>
<br><a href="#Final">Final Considerations</a>


<P>
The scheme to impose a government-controlled health
care system on the American public was not buried by the 1994
elections.  It's not even dead.  Advocates of Hillary-style health
care, stung by defeat in 1993, have reformulated their strategy,
changed their terminology, and shifted their venue.  Instead of
a frontal assault on the private provision of health care, they
are now sneaking their statist health agenda through the statehouse
and schoolhouse door.</FONT>
<P>
  Health care reform has been reincarnated as welfare
and education reform.  With financial support from major private
philanthropies like the Robert Wood Johnson, Henry J. Kaiser Family,
Annie E. Casey, and Rockefeller foundations, and the Pew Charitable
Trusts, proponents of national health care have reorganized and
repackaged their ideas into a number of state-based programs.
Instead of universal health care mandates on an entire population,
they propose a new framework of public-private education and welfare
partnerships.  And since these are touted as serving the &quot;needs&quot;
of children, lawmakers find them much harder to oppose.</FONT>
<P>
* * * * *</FONT>
<P>
  The Pennsylvania General Assembly's House of Representatives
recently passed a resolution, introduced with bipartisan support,
which authorized its Education Committee to investigate how the
state's public school system was being used to provide health
programs for students and their families.  Hearings were held
last year, and many legislators were shocked to discover that
in several districts school-based health clinics were already
providing extensive health services.  These clinics were established
and funded to provide a battery of services without the knowledge
or consent of the Pennsylvania General Assembly.</FONT>
<P>
  The Pennsylvania state legislature is learning
what other state legislators are learning:  that its constitutional
authority has been ignored and its prerogatives undercut by officials
in the Clinton Administration and the National Governors' Association
who are working with bureaucrats in state departments of education,
health, and public welfare, and with officials from private philanthropic
foundations, including the Robert Wood Johnson Foundation, the
Henry J. Kaiser Family Foundation, the Pew Charitable Trusts,
the Kellogg Foundation, and the Annie E. Casey Foundation.  (For
more information on the Casey Foundation, which is headed by United
Parcel Service Chairman Kent C. Nelson, see the December 1995
issue of Organization Trends.)</FONT>
<P>
  Legislatures are also discovering that programs
and proposals that claim to be intended for America's children
actually represent the spearhead of a renewed assault on private
health care.  Hundreds of boxes of documents labeled &quot;confidential&quot;
assembled by the once secret and largely still mysterious Clinton
Health Care Task Force in 1993, which are as yet uncatalogued,
but in the custody of the National Archives in College Park, Maryland,
disclose the Administration's thinking.  They contain extensive
references to child health programs as a fallback position in
case the Administration failed to secure a comprehensive and universal
national health system.  As a matter of public policy and political
strategy, the Clintonites consciously had decided to use children
to phase-in health programs ultimately intended for all Americans.</FONT>
<P>
  The documents suggest that the Clinton Administration
looked  carefully at Goals 2000, an education initiative begun
during the Bush Administration, and Medicaid, the government health
program for the poor jointly funded under complicated formulas
by the states and the federal government.  These programs would
be the vehicles to integrate and coordinate publicly-funded health
and human service programs.  </FONT>
<P>
  They would use school districts as delivery sites
for providing greatly expanded health services.  And they would
be responsive to signals from private philanthropic foundations
that would provide start-up funds that, when combined with subsequent
tax dollars, could draw almost every American citizen into a web
of new government health programs. <BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<hr>
<a name="Children"</a>
<h3>The Children's Initiative:  It Takes A Child To Disguise
A Policy</h3>

  The Clinton Administration has elevated into an
art form the use of children as tools of social policy.  By devising
new social programs so that children are the first beneficiaries
of government entitlements, Administration policymakers get the
public to acquiesce to programs that have far more ambitious goals.
Hillary Rodham Clinton's new book on children, It Takes A Village,
is meant to be a cozy literary paraphrase of Administration policies.</FONT>
<P>
  In 1988, the Rockefeller Foundation, the Robert
Wood Johnson Foundation, and the Henry J. Kaiser Family Foundation
provided grant monies that enabled the National Governors' Association
(NGA) to produce a manual for Goals 2000, a series of vague pledges
by the states to set more rigorous standards for public education.
One year later, the Bush administration and the NGA, chaired
by then-Arkansas Governor Bill Clinton, held an &quot;Education
Summit&quot; that further developed but did not clarify the goal
of national education standards.  </FONT>
<P>
  In 1994, while the Clintons' health reform proposals
were flailing, Goals 2000 became law.  Now a national mantra,
Goals 2000 is invoked by many in the education establishment to
justify the latest fads flowing through academia, e.g., outcomes-based
education.  Less noted is how it has been used as a cover to authorize
programs in health care.</FONT>
<P>
  Federal and state agencies and private nonprofit
organizations are currently seeking public and private funds for
the &quot;The Children's Initiative,&quot; which appears to be
a name assigned by the Philadelphia-based Pew Charitable Trusts
to describe the collaborative efforts of private foundations working
with government to develop, coordinate and support a panopoly
of health service programs in the nation's public school systems
_ a plan almost Byzantine in its complexity.  Particularly in
treating problems of student behavior, these programs have begun
raising eyebrows.</FONT>
<P>
  Under this initiative, Goals 2000 is creating a
system in which children selected by teachers are regularly tested
for emotional, social, mental, and physical disorders in clinics
established within public schools.  These disorders include what
is called Attention Deficit Disorder (ADD) or Attention Deficit
Hyperactivity Disorder (ADHD).  Once children are diagnosed and
labelled as subject to this condition according to a scale of
supposed &quot;norms&quot; of mental and emotional health, school
health officials have the authority to treat them by prescribing
and administering such medications as Ritalin, Valium, Lorazepam
and Prozac.  These officials derive their authority from new,
looser prescription-writing standards developed under Robert Wood
Johnson Foundation initiatives to liberalize state restrictions
on who can prescribe medications, thus allowing nurse practitioners
and physician assistants to prescribe drugs.  The consent of parents
is sometimes required, and sometimes not.  </FONT>
<P>
  Goals 2000 proposals receive funding from federal
programs, including Medicaid and Maternal and Child Health (Title
X) block grants, comparable state programs, and philanthropic
foundations.  Some school districts and state legislatures have
resisted Goals 2000.  And at least four states, including Virginia,
have refused to apply for federal funds to implement it.  But
many Governors, unable to resist the lure of the hard coin, are
using Executive Orders to implement state programs to meet Goals
2000.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<hr>
<a name="Quiz"></a>
<h3>The School Quiz: It's Different</h3>

  How did the problem of student misbehavior in school
become a national health issue?  In 1991, the U.S. Department
of Education formally recognized ADHD as a handicap under the
Individuals with Disabilities Education Act and Section 504 of
the 1973 Rehabilitation Act.  The Department directed all state
education officers to ensure that local school districts established
procedures to screen and identify ADHD children and provide them
with special educational and psychological services.  Naturally,
&quot;school-wide&quot; interventions are favored by the Department.
Programs are now being developed for all children in public schools
and their parents.  </FONT>
<P>
  The parents of elementary school children in Gateway
School District in Pennsylvania recently came face to face with
the implications of all this.  Two projects named &quot;Pharmacological
and Psychosocial Treatment for ADHD&quot; and &quot;Community-Based
Treatment for ADHD: Summer Treatment Programs and School-Wide
Interventions&quot; were funded by a private foundation grant
to the University of Pittsburgh and the Gateway School District
in Pennsylvania.  The Pittsburgh-based foundation will not allow
its name to be disclosed.  The federal National Institutes of
Mental Health provided matching public grant monies, in amounts
as yet to be disclosed.   </FONT>
<P>
  One portion of the project is called the Pittsburgh
School Wide Intervention Model (PSWIM).  The Principal of Pitcairn
Elementary School, Alex J. Balla, described PSWIM in a letter
to parents:  &quot;Many parts of the PSWIM program are designed
to help children get along better with one another.  One part
uses a procedure called sociometrics, in which children are asked
to answer questions about the kids in their class.  Each child
... will be asked about who their best friends are, who they do
not want to be friends with, and to rate how much they like the
other kids in the class ... All information is kept confidential
and children will be told that it is very important that they
do not discuss their answers with the other kids.&quot;</FONT>
<P>
  The PSWIM program produces daily &quot;behavior&quot;
report cards and a &quot;behavior&quot; Honor Roll.  &quot;Positive&quot;
report cards go to students who do their homework, return homework
assignment sheets signed by a parent and &quot;break two or fewer
rules during the day.&quot;  There are only six rules, and all
are benign (e.g. be respectful of others; stay in assigned seat;
work quietly; and obey adults).  </FONT>
<P>
  The Behavior Honor Roll seems merely to codify
the tradition of &quot;teacher's pet.&quot;  Honor Roll kids ages
5 to 8 &quot;earn special class jobs and/or privileges,&quot;
and wear special badges.  Nothing out of the ordinary.  However,
PSWIM also requires each teacher to fill out an eight page &quot;Teacher
Rating Scale&quot; questionnaire for each five to eight year old
and check the applicable descriptions:</FONT>
<P>

<ul>
<li> has run away from home overnight at least twice
while living in a parental or parental surrogate home.
<P>
<li> often initiates physical fights with other members of his or her household.
<p>
<li> has forced someone into sexual activity.
<P>
<li> often stays out at night despite parental prohibitions.
<P>
<li> has stolen while confronting a victim (e.g. mugging,
purse snatching, extortion, armed robbery).
<P>
<li> teases or calls other children names.
<P>
<li> is disliked by other children.
<P>
<li> is simply ignored by other children.
</font>
<P>
<font size=2 > For five to eight year olds?  Reading the list,
one is struck by the gross disparity in behaviors.  The descriptions
range from normal childhood pranks and grievances to criminality.
Where would teachers have access to such information?</font>  
<P>
<font size =2>  The answer is that comprehensive health and education
data on all the children who participate in PSWIM is contained
in records at the Western Psychiatric Institute and Clinic at
the University of Pittsburgh.  Under the professional services
agreement between the University and Gateway School District,
PSWIM was implemented by an individual with a Masters degree in
education who was supervised by an individual with a Ph.D. _ not
an M.D. _ at Western Psychiatric Institute.  The individual with
the Masters degree interviewed the children in order to gather
the data.</FONT>
<P>
  Alarmed parents from PSWIM area elementary schools
protested the program, its taxpayer funding, and the use of undisclosed
private grant money.  Concerned parents met with baffled legislators
and recalcitrant state education officials, and made appearances
on local media.  They demanded that the program be ended.  It
was terminated on November 21, 1995.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<hr>
<a name="Policy"></a>
<h3>Education Policy: <br>
Surrogate for Health Care</h3>

  Though it failed to pass health care reform in
1993, Congress in 1994 passed three major pieces of education
reform legislation sought by the Clinton Administration:</font> <p> 
<B>Goals 2000:</b><p>

<ol>
<li>Educate America Act;<p> 
<li> School-to-Work Opportunities Act;<p>
<li> The Improving America's Schools Act of 1994, which reauthorized
the Elementary and Secondary Education Act (ESEA).<p>
</ol></font>
<P>
  The way the Clinton Administration has implemented
these laws reveals that its health reform agenda did not fail
_ it only failed to pass the Congress.  Education reform has become
a road to health reform.  State agencies and private foundations
are the Administration's willing accomplices in skirting the legislative
process to change health policy.</FONT>
<P>
  Thirteen states now participate in the U.S. Department
of Education's Integrated Services Project, &quot;Creating Schools
That Work for Everyone&quot; (CSTWE).  CSTWE was created by the
Department of Education in 1994.  It aims to integrate within
the public school system many health and human services provided
by government.  This includes services from Medicaid programs,
Aid to Families with Dependent Children, Maternal and Child Health
block grants, and services created by new monies available to
school systems under the three new education acts: Goals 2000,
the School-to-Work law, and the reauthorization of ESEA.  The
thirteen states currently participating in CSTWE are California,
Florida, Kentucky, Louisiana, Maine, Michigan, Minnesota, Mississippi,
New Mexico, Oregon, Pennsylvania, Tennessee, and Texas.</FONT>
<P>
  CSTWE project consultants have been hired by the
U.S. Department of Education.  They include several Washington,
DC-based 501(c)(3) organizations:  The Institute for Health Services
Management, the National Alliance for Restructuring Education
(NARE), the New American Schools Development Corporation (NASDC),
and the National School Health Education Coalition.  NARE and
NASDC are also working with the states of Arkansas, Kentucky,
New York, Vermont, and Washington, city governments in Rochester
(NY), White Plains (NY), and San Diego, and the Farrell Area School
District of Pittsburgh.  NARE claims that its state and city work
accounts for twelve percent of the nation's schoolchildren.  These
consultants are now embroiled in the New York State Attorney General's
investigation of the National Center for Education and the Economy
and its ties to prominent political figures, including Hillary
Clinton, North Carolina Governor James Hunt, former New York Governor
Mario Cuomo, and health care czar Ira Magaziner.  In part, the
investigation concerns payments made to Mrs. Clinton by the Rochester-based
Center.</FONT>
<P>
<hr>
<a name="Brave"></a>
<h3>Kentucky's Brave New World</h3>

  While it is too early to say exactly what CSTWE
will accomplish, information uncovered through open records requests
in Kentucky give some indication of what its proponents seek.</FONT>
<P>
  For instance, Wade Mountz, Chairman of the Kentucky
Commission on Families and Children (set up by Governor Brereton
Jones to help implement the controversial Kentucky Education Reform
Act), has defined his Commission's goal as the &quot;provision
of a wide range of education, health, mental health, and social
services that are delivered in a coordinated and comprehensive
way to families and their children.&quot;  The Commission has
focussed its work on school districts in Louisville and Owensboro.
In seeking a grant from the Annie E. Casey Foundation, one which
required a matching grant of taxpayer dollars, Mountz wrote a
March 30, 1995 grant application to Casey's Associate Director
Anthony Cippollone.  After discussing the need to coordinate health
and human services in the school system, Mountz explained why
Kentucky was the right state for an investment of Casey Foundation
money:</FONT>
<P>
  &quot;We will have a change in administration in
December 1995.  The Commissions' [sic] job is to produce selected
local communities whose plans are so attractive that the new administration
and the legislature will be compelled to cooperate with the approach&quot;
(emphasis added).</FONT>
<P>
  What sorts of plans are envisioned?  The Kentucky
Legislative Research Commission in 1992 hired a consulting firm,
Leadership Development Associates, to assist the Kentucky Task
Force on Education Reform.  It proposed six alternative models
for local governments and school districts to govern the web of
human service programs envisioned by the Kentucky legislature:
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>

<ol>
<li> Total Educational Governance System for Lifetime Learning
<P>
<li> Reconstituting Local Government for Education and Well-Being;
<P>
<li>Educational Development Territories;
<P>
<li> Large Regional Operating Districts;
<P>
<li> Fine-Tuning the Present System; and
<P>
<li> The Unitary District Plan.<br>
</font>
<p>
<br>
</ol>
  The consultants, in the syntax expected of their
sort, explained that Model One's lifetime learning approach &quot;is
a much larger expectation for each citizen.&quot;  It suggested:
&quot;a reconsideration of the compulsory education requirements
pushing taxpayer responsibility both downward and upward through
the age ranges.  Obviously lifetime learning has tremendous implications
for educational finance moving away from traditional concepts
of funding toward new ideas such as individual entitlements to
be expended throughout the lifetime.  Each citizen would have
a lifetime learning account to draw on as needed.&quot;</FONT>
<P>
  Model Two, &quot;Reconstituting Government for
Education and Well-Being,&quot; strikes a tone reminiscent of
Brave New World:  The consultants imagine local-level &quot;Chancellors
of Well-Being&quot; who would govern as elected officials.  Leadership
Development Associates explained, &quot;Well-being does not have
the same political connotation as welfare often does.&quot;  The
Chancellors would be charged with protecting and enhancing community
well-being.  As the consultants explained:</FONT>
<P>
  &quot;Although the nation's commitment to general
well-being is anchored in the Constitution, we have treated it
casually, almost with indifference.  We have created units of
local government, such as school districts, and charged them with
part of the responsibility for well-being, but not the whole of
it.  Schooling may well be the flagship of a flotilla of approaches
to well-being but it is not the all of it.  Schooling must be
joined more fundamentally by other contributors of well-being
....&quot;</FONT>
<P>
  The proposal recommends that the Kentucky General
Assembly appoint a permanent &quot;Joint Well-Being Oversight
Committee,&quot; and replace the existing State Board of Elementary
and Secondary Education with a new fifteen member &quot;State
Board of Well-Being.&quot;  The State Board of Well-Being would
be led by the &quot;State Chancellor of Well-Being,&quot; which
runs the &quot;Division of Well-Being Services&quot; _ &quot;a
range of well-being oriented programs and services, including
many of those that traditionally have been offered through the
department of education.&quot;<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<hr>
<a name="Medicaid"></a>
<h3>The Medicaid Program in Pennsylvania:  Out of Control</h3>

  Officials in the Clinton Administration's Department
of Health and Human Services, including Heath Care Financing Adminstration
chief Bruce C. Vladeck (a former Henry J. Kaiser Family Foundation
trustee and former vice president of the Robert Wood Johnson Foundation),
have indicated plans to expand Medicaid eligibility to 40 million
Americans.  By granting &quot;waivers&quot; from Medicaid's eligibility
restrictions, the Administration has nearly achieved that goal.
More than half the states currently operate their programs under
such waivers, which expand the definitions of the word &quot;provider.&quot;
Even school districts can now be considered &quot;Medicaid providers&quot;
and they can bill state and federal Medicaid authorities to be
reimbursed for services they provide.  </FONT>
<P>
  School-based health service programs take advantage
of Medicaid by drawing on its &quot;Early Intervention Services&quot;
program which offers a benefit known as &quot;Early Periodic Screening,
Diagnosis, and Treatment&quot; (EPSDT).  EPSDT provides vision,
hearing, and dental testing.  It also provides &quot;other necessary
health care, diagnostic services, treatment, and other measures
. . . to correct or ameliorate defects and physical and mental
illnesses and conditions discovered by the screening services
. . . whether or not such services are covered under the state
plan.&quot;  The 1989 Budget Reconciliation Act required the states
to make the EPSDT benefit available to all eligible Medicaid recipients
age 21 and under, even where a state's Medicaid plan does not
provide state funding for reimbursement.  In such cases, the federal
government must cover EPSDT payments.  </FONT>
<P>
  The law further provides that the state must take
&quot;effective&quot; steps to inform all those eligible for EPSDT
of its availability.  Moreover, a D.C. federal court has held
that the statute is sufficiently specific to create &quot;an enforceable
right of action&quot; under the 1964 Civil Rights Act.  </FONT>
<P>
  EPSDT is out of control.  In Pennsylvania, the
legislators did not know how it was affecting school decisionmaking
until they began to hear from parents.  That state's Goals 2000
plan specifically identifies school-based clinics as essential
to achieve its first Goal, &quot;Readiness for School.&quot; 
And an October 5, 1994 memorandum from the Pennsylvania Commissioner
for Elementary and Secondary Education, Joseph F. Bard, to Pennsylvania
School Administrators and Intermediate Unit Executive Directors,
describes how school officials will achieve the goal:  &quot;The
Department has initiated...a program which will allow [school
districts, intermediate units, and approved private schools]...to
obtain federal reimbursement for administrative costs incurred
in providing health related services to medical assistance eligible
students.</FONT>
<P>
  &quot;The use of these funds to supplement the
district's health program will not only provide additional need
health services to the district's student population, but will
increase the district's expenditures for health care services
and thus increase further drawdown of administrative funds under
Title XIX.&quot; </FONT>
<P>
  Pennsylvania's Department of Public Welfare has
applied to the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services to
amend the state's Medicaid plan to expand Early Intervention Services
so that schools can request reimbursement beyond the minimum vision,
hearing, and dental tests.  In a June 29, 1995 letter to HHS,
Deputy Secretary Nancy R. Thaler created a virtual &quot;wish
list&quot; of ten program services she would like to offer: social
work, audiology, nursing services, occupational therapy, physical
therapy, psychological services, speech pathology, initial &quot;early
intervention&quot; screening, special instruction, and service
coordination.  Under this proposal, school districts could bill
Medicaid for up to 20 units of service activity per year at $20.00
per unit for each program service it offered.  In other words,
Medicaid might be required to reimburse every school district
up to $4,000 annually per child eligible for the full list of
services.  </FONT>
<P>
  Currently six school districts _ Farrell, Towanda,
Allentown, Philadelphia, Lancaster, and Central Fulton _ operate
school-based health clinics under a Medicaid waiver.  Pennsylvania
still awaits approval of its wish list, but these districts currently
provide the following EPSDT services:  mental health/counseling,
health education, physical examinations/screening, anticipatory
health guidance, referral/tracking of health problems, and dental
services.  <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<hr>
<a name="Robert Wood"></a>
<h3>Robert Wood Johnson Foundation: &quot;Leveraging&quot;
Government Funding</h3>

  The Robert Wood Johnson Foundation (RWJF) began
its Mental Health Services for Youth Program in 1989, the same
year Congress authorized federal payment for EPSDT services. 
RWJF grants from this program to state agencies in Pennsylvania
and Kentucky are responsible for creating the procedures that
enable school districts to apply for and receive federal Medicaid
reimbursement for mental health services.</FONT>
<P>
  In 1989, the Johnson Foundation reached the one
billion dollar mark in grants distributed, a goal that took seventeen
years to achieve.  In 1995, just six years later, the Princeton,
New Jersey-based philanthropy awarded its two billionth grant
dollar. The Foundation has said, &quot;The work accomplished,
more than the money awarded, is the true measure of RWJF's achievements.&quot;
That claim bears examination.  The Foundation proudly extolls
the practice of &quot;leveraging public funds.&quot;  Not content
to wait for public agencies to pick up the costs of programs it
has started, the Foundation often requires co-funding committments
from government before it initiates new programs.   </FONT>
<P>
  For instance, RWJF awarded the state of Kentucky
a $100,000 planning grant from the Mental Health Services for
Youth Program.  Kentucky subsequently received Phase I and Phase
II Implementation grants of more than $2,400,000.  The Foundation
has stated, &quot;The major objective . . . is to improve mental
health services for seriously mentally ill children and youth
by developing comprehensive services systems under the aegis of
multi-agency, state-community partnerships that can make major
changes in financing, organization, and delivery of services.&quot;
 </FONT>
<P>
  Clearly, affecting state government policy is central
to RWJF's grantmaking.  The Foundation has indicated that it will
give priority to projects that demonstrate &quot;evidence of collaboration
of multiple agencies at both the state and community levels, including
agreements with institutional care providers to assure appropriate
movement among levels of care,&quot; and &quot;a high likelihood
that the project will continue following the conclusion of Foundation
support and that lasting changes will be made in the state's mental
health services delivery and financing systems.&quot; </FONT>
<P>
  Foundation documents are even more specific.  For
Kentucky, they reveal that &quot;every grant dollar is expected
to leverage five dollars in public monies.&quot;  By carefully
using its grant dollars to promote interagency agreements on mental
health for youth, RWJF is well on its way to achieving comprehensive
health reform in this area in Kentucky.</FONT>
<P>
  How does RWJF secure the cooperation of state officials?
Kentucky's participation was secured after North Carolina Governor
James Hunt, chairman of RWJF's national advisory board for its
Mental Health Services for Youth program, wrote Kentucky's then-Governor
Wallace Wilkinson and invited him to apply for a Foundation grant.
A grateful Wilkinson responded, &quot;The goals of the Robert
Wood Johnson Foundation Initiative are very much within the mission
of the CYSB [Kentucky Children's and Youth Services Bureau].&quot;
 </FONT>
<P>
  The Robert Wood Johnson Foundation has used the
power of its private money to rearrange one state's public finances.
It has not been shy about what it expects from Kentucky state
lawmakers.  In Kentucky's proposal for grant funds _ which funds
it received _ the state Secretary for the Cabinet for Human Resources
promised:  &quot;We will be seeking major legislation that sets
in statute for the whole state the system of care for children
and youth with severe emotional problems.  Legitimating this effort
in statute will assure that changing administrations and their
shifting priorities will not hinder the system of care effort.&quot;</FONT>
<P>
  In 1990, the Kentucky Legislature passed a bare-bones
statute that was intended to apply to 54 identified children who
had severe mental health problems.  Yet RWJF grants of more than
$2.4 million plus state and federal funding in excess of $10 million
have had their effect.  Because almost any child can be examined
under the EPSDT benefit for &quot;mental health&quot; problems
in Kentucky, local school districts and state agencies can now
tap into both federal and state Medicaid funds.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<hr>
<a name="Final"></a>
<h3>Final Considerations</h3>
<P>
  It is time for Congress and state legislatures
to re-examine how children have become pawns in political struggles
over power and money.  They must also exercise rigorous legislative
oversight of state applications for federal Medicaid &quot;waivers.&quot;
Lawmakers need to examine whether it is appropriate for private
foundations to distribute grants to government agencies.  And
Congress should consider enlarging the federal Anti-Deficiency
Act, which prohibits the use of private monies to create and pay
for new staff positions at public agencies _ thereby creating
a deficiency since the taxpayers are eventually expected to foot
the bill.  Finally, a vigilant citizenry and press need to apply
more scrutiny to foundations, demanding greater accountability
than currently exists.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<I><FONT COLOR=#000000>Genevieve M. Young, is a Washington, D.C.
attorney in private practice specializing in health issues.</FONT></I>
</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT15-B10-115</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA033-000676-B007-87</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.empower.org:80/crc/trends/ot-0296.html 204.71.237.79 19970209183442 text/html 25126
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Sunday, 09-Feb-97 18:35:21 GMT
