<I><B><FONT SIZE=4>April 1996</FONT></B></I>
<P><a name="top"></a>
<h2>The Ronald McDonald House</h2>
<b><I>The House That Love Built</I></b><BR>
<p>
<B><FONT SIZE=2><a href="#name">By Gwen Vereen Purtill & Patrick D. Purtill, Jr</a></FONT></B>
<P>
  Debbie Wargos voice was cheerful and warm and she got straight to the point.  I was calling three minutes after my husband and I were to have arrived to interview her at the Ronald McDonald House.<p>
  Gwen! I was just taking your name in vain. Are we going to have to reschedule?
  We had come down with an ugly flu last night, I explained, and didnt think we ought to share it with the kids.<p>
  Yes, she agreed, wed have to ask you not to come in under the circumstances. So many of the children here have suppressed immune systems. We agreed to have a preliminary talk by phone and visit 
the House when we were well.<p>
  Debbie is the executive director of the Ronald McDonald House, a 22-bedroom facility in northeast Washington, D.C. Since 1980, it has provided a home away from home to families of children being treated for life-threatening illness in any of the areas hospitals. A family can stay indefinitely as long as their child is under active treatment. This hospitality extends to children who are receiving outpatient care such as chemotherapy or radiation.  The House serves families that live at least an hour away from the hospital where the child is being treated, or that face other circumstances that making it impossible for them to get back and forth. <p>
  The House itself is a large and inviting 1920s style structure, comprised of a main house and pavilion situated on a two-acre plot that allows for a large playground in back. On the ground floor of the main house are generous gathering rooms, the dining room and kitchen. The pavilion bridge houses a 
meditation/consultation room and a small library; on the ground floor of the pavilion is a television/playroom.<p>
  During its fifteen years of operation, the D.C. House has served nearly eight thousand families. The sixteenth of the now more than 160 Ronald McDonald Houses worldwide, the D.C. House is owned and operated by Ronald McDonald House Charities of Greater Washington D.C., a nonprofit organization. 
Roughly 50 percent of those served by the DC House are children from military families being treated at Walter Reed Hospital in Washington.
<p>
<h3>Missys Story</h3>
<p>
  Missy Terry is from such a family. Missy and two of her three brothers and sisters were born in Korea to a military couple. Missys mother, Tara, left the service when  she and her husband Mark were sent to separate duty stations. In January 1995, Mark was posted to Korea for a second time and they decided that 
Tara and the children would move to Illinois to be near Taras family.
  In early March 1995, Tara took four-year-old Missy to see her doctor because she had what looked like a mild cold and had started waking up at night complaining of headaches. Unable to find anything wrong, 
the doctor sent her home. But a few days later, Missys lymph nodes began to swell and her face was noticeably puffy. Tara took her to the emergency room and doctors warned that Missy might not survive the night. Mark was on a plane home from Korea the next morning.<p>
  The diagnosis was Acute Lymphoblastic Leukemia in which the bone-marrow and other blood-forming organs produce increased numbers of white blood cells. Missys white cell count was 1.2 million, with 92 percent leukemic cells. Three times Missy went through a process that removed the blood from her body 
and cleaned it. After all this, Missys white cell count came down to 350,000seven times what is considered high risk and roughly thirty-five times what is considered normal. Missys ability to fight off infection often is so low that everyday matters like using a drinking glass after her sisters or brother become seriously dangerous.<p>
  Nearly every day for three months, Missy and her family made the 110-mile drive to the hospital in St. Louis where she was being treated. It was a constant drain, remembers Tara. She now wonders why no one at the hospital suggested they stay at the Ronald McDonald House in St. Louis.<p>
   Each time the family adjusted to the demands of a regimen of treatment, it seemed that they were buffeted by something new. At first there was only the shock, but then Missy somehow lived through the initial phase of treatment. Then, Mark and Tara were told that Missy would have to have a broviac (an in-
dwelling catheter) implanted in her chest; it seemed like the end of the world. Next began the day-to day business of contending with chemotherapy, while watching their little girl lose her hair. <p>
  At first, Missy was as frightened as they were. She wasnt feeling all that sick, but suddenly teams of doctors were descending on her. Now, Tara says, Missy is not afraid of anything. She knows how to take care of the broviac, and when a nurse is careless, she tells her what she is doing wrong. At home, she does 
the heparin push in her own tube and always remembers her pills. Tara describes Missy as bright, energetic and an attention seeker. It is easy for onlookers to forget, but kids will be kids. Tara and Mark still have to 
discipline her occasionally, but it is hard. Missy is not allowed to misbehave. But now, says Tara, she and Mark evaluate the situation more generously before deciding that it really is important that Missy is told no.<p>
  In late June of 1995, the family was transferred to Ft. Belvoir, south of Washington, D.C., and Missy became a patient at Walter Reed, one of the armys three major hospitals. The move exacted a terrible emotional toll on the family. It was horrible, Tara says, We knew no one. <p>
  The family went directly to the hospital when they arrived in Washington because Missy had an infection. She stayed there for twenty-three days. The family had no place to live. The first night in town they paid $85 for a hotel room that Tara describes as unpleasant. Taking matters into their own hands they asked a hospital social worker to place them in a Ronald McDonald House. He made the referral, and they stayed there for three weeks until Missy was released.<p>
  During those three weeks, the family stayed in the downstairs bone marrow apartment of the D.C. Ronald McDonald House. The Terrys consider themselves private people, and did not especially relish the idea of staying in a group environment. But the staff helped them to get over their discomfort. At the House there was always someone to talk to who was concerned about their needs. Even now as Tara gets more involved with support organizations, she says that only at the Ronald McDonald House is everyone consistently supportive. <p>
  Tara was especially impressed that the House takes it in stride when residents fail to appreciate what is being done for them. They ask nothing but that you clean up after yourself. Some people do not even do that. They really seem to understand the stress level better even than hospital staff.<p>
 One day, in particular, the Terrys were exhausted and tense. A woman in the kitchen spoke sharply to Missy, who was out of the hospital on a pass. Mark came downstairs and blew his top. Later he went to Barbara Silverman, the Resident Manager, to apologize for making a scene.  Barbara was unruffled; she understood his stress.<p>
  During that time, Missy was in treatment at the hospital for 72 hour periods. But occasionally the hospital would let her leave on a pass for eight hours. Back at the House she could be with her parents and see her brothers and sisters who were at the House all the time.<p>
  Tara thinks her family has been very proactive in doing research and looking into Missys options. But she says the Ronald McDonald House was their only source of support during that period. Without it there would have been more crises. Because you are in the hospital so much, you see a lot. It really gets depressing. But at least we had a place to go. At the Ronald McDonald House, we could see a friendly face, talk to people, and vent our frustration.<p>
  While the family was emotionally needy, they saw many families at the House who were in much worse financial shape. The staff of the Ronald McDonald House gave one family Christmas presents and food vouchers. Tara especially felt for the overseas families that were separated because usually only one parent 
could accompany the child to the U.S.<p>
  After Missys initial stay at the Ronald McDonald House, the family moved to Ft. Belvoir in Northern Virginia, forty-seven miles on the other side of Washington from Missys hospital. If her other children were not in school, they would still be staying at the House. Tara says it is the first place she will look to if Missy should relapse or if Mark is transferred. <p>
  Missy is on a high dose chemotherapy regimen, and has lost her hair. People often mistake her for a little boy, says Tara. One day in the park, kids made fun of her hair, so now she wears a baseball cap all the time. But despite having tubes in her chest, she is very active; she runs and plays. You get to a point in all 
this of feeling sorry for yourself. But she is so strong, so happy, and so outgoingshe keeps us going. She has lost so muchher dance classes and pre-school. She has done very wellbetter than we have.<p>
  Missy currently is in a two-year maintenance phase of her treatment by experimental chemotherapy. They do most of the maintenance at home, including the chemo, which is administered through her leg. She only has to go into the hospital about three days every month. Doctors say Missy has about a 30% 
chance of making it through the maintenance regimen without a relapse. The family had a scare near the end of January when Missys white blood cell count dropped suddenly. If there is a relapse, the initial thirty-day induction stage of intensive treatment in the hospital starts again. It is also likely that doctors 
would prescribe a risky bone marrow transplant, which they have not done yet because none of Missys brothers or sisters are a match.  In either case, the family plans to spend their nights at the Ronald McDonald House while Missy sleeps. <p>
  If all goes well, there will be a final five-year phase of treatment. But it will be at least another seven years before Missy is out of the woods. Meanwhile, Tara now tells other families about the House because she thinks that it can help them through the crisis. When you need them, she says, it really makes the 
difference between whether the situation is bearable or unbearable.<p>
  Tara still feels isolated here. The couple made a few friends at the Ronald McDonald House. But they are finding that it is hard to start new friendships  because they are so emotionally needy and often exhausted. As a result Tara has started working with support groups. At least  everyone there is in the same boat. The House is sponsoring an Easter egg hunt in April, and Tara intends to take the children. Even if you are not staying at the House anymore, they are always open to you if you need it, she says.<p>
<h3>Full House</h3>
  <p>
The week before we visited the D.C. Ronald McDonald House, only five of its twenty-two rooms were occupied. But by the time we arrived on a Monday afternoon, Barbara, the resident manager, was juggling families and rooms. It is impossible to tell from day to day what the need will be. During busy times like 
these, the House has its medical priorities. The original mission of the Ronald McDonald Houses gave cancer and leukemia patients the highest priority as well as any child in an intensive care unit. The level of priority works its way down from there. Debbie tells us that they would never turn away a high priority 
family. If necessary, they will look for a hotel in the area willing to donate a room while the House is full. <p>
  When space is available, grandparents and other relatives may stay at the House. Like immediate family members, they are asked to make the customary $10 per night donation. However, reservations for extended family members are handled on a day-to-day basis.<p>
  Families must be referred by the hospital that is treating the child. Usually a hospital social worker or sometimes a doctor or nurse makes the referral. No walk-ins are accepted at Ronald McDonald Houses. There are few problems because the social workers assess whether the family is looking for a hotel or 
needs a temporary home. Occasionally a family cannot fit into the group setting, but  very rarely is anyone asked to leave. When  family members check in, they go through an orientation during which are asked to agree to, and sign, a handbook specifying  the House rules. Occasionally, a family will decide not to stay, 
but that doesnt happen very often.<p>
   Most families stay for two or more weeks. They live in a group setting and are responsible for doing their own laundry and cooking.  A cheerful plaque that hangs on an interior wall as you enter the kitchen sums up the philosophy and organization of the entire operation: This is a self-cleaning kitchen. Please clean up after yourself. Opposite,  numbered cupboards store the food purchased by families.  A common pantry is provided although the families buy most of their own food. Barbara coordinates emergency provisions for the pantry from local vendors, clubs, organizations, and individuals.<p>
  Most people welcome the opportunity to engage in the normal activities of daily lifecooking their own meals, doing laundry, cleaning up common areas. They want to feel they are doing something useful for their family and others at a time when they may feel helpless in the face of a childs illness.<p>

<h3>A Surrogate Community</h3>
<p>
  There are plenty of restaurants and hotels in the Washington area, but most families simply cannot afford to eat out every night and stay in hotels for a prolonged periodespecially if they already face large medical bills. Hotels leave families isolated at a time when they most need emotional support.  Kate Shafer, a social worker at Childrens Hospital, says the  House provides an opportunity for normal interaction for couples and extended family. They  can sleep restfully  knowing they are five minutes away from their sick child. And the child can sleep soundly knowing mom and dad are minutes away. 
According to Shafer, parents away from home and family find a naturally supportive community of 
people who are uniquely sensitive to their needs.<p>
  Staff believe that this temporary community, while ones own is out of reach, is one of the most important 
services the house provides. Families can sit down together over breakfast and informally compare notes 
on what to expect as treatment progresses. Newer patients can ask those who know the ropes about hospital 
services and staff, or they can find out how to deal with practical problems that arise as they try to take care 
of a child who is in transition from the hospital.<p>
  Like most places that cater to children, Ronald McDonald Houses go all out for holidays. Groups bring in 
Christmas presents or Valentines Day treats. Some will bring little favors or bake cookies. At Halloween a 
group always comes to decorate the stairwell, and the kids go trick-or-treating at Catholic University a few 
blocks away. When we visited, the House was celebrating a mothers birthday.  Barbara provided  a cake, 
and small presents were waiting to be opened. In preparation for Valentines Day, a table in the hall held 
dozens of favors, prepared by volunteers, awaiting the return of the families that evening.<p>
  Giving the House a homey feel is crucial to its mission. Much of that feeling is achieved by the staff and 
volunteers who keep the atmosphere informal. But while hospital staff often try to keep things informal  no 
one has ever left a hospital thinking it had a homey feeling. In this House children are allowed to play. It 
is a place where kids can just be themselvesa place where they feel comfortable enough to allow their 
thinning hair to show. Even structurally, the House encourages community. Rooms dont form an insular 
world the way they do in hotels. There is only one central kitchen. The bathrooms are shared. Telephones 
and televisions are in common areas so families are more or less forced to go out, just as they would at 
home.<p>
  Because of this, the supportive bonds formed at the House often grow into lifetime friendships. Early in 
its history, the House had a number of children with extremely serious cancers, and many of them did not 
make it. Some of those families still keep in touch, and even get together for holidays.<p>
  A very ill teenage girl has been at the D.C. House with her father for several months. Her mother died 
several years ago. When she first came to the House, she told Barbara that all of her friends had dropped 
her because they were unable to understand what she was going through. She has since become attached  to 
the staff and to some of the mothers and children staying at the House, and they to her.<p>
  We are her friends, says Barbara. If you asked her whether she would like to be here or at home, at this 
stage she probably would say here. She was in the hospital, but when it looked as if she was certain to get 
better, she asked if she could stay here during her physical therapy. Shes more comfortable hereexcept 
for Max, her dog. She misses Max.
<p>
<h3>Day by Day</h3>
<p>
  While Debbie Wargo goes out into the community looking for financial and other help, Barbara works 
with the families and the volunteers. Her job is to keep everything functioning and everyone living as one 
big happy family. Says Barbara, she raises all the money and I get to spend it.  Barbara tries to have 
volunteers on hand from 9:00 a.m. to 9:00 p.m. each day to do everything from answering the telephones 
to checking in guests, checking rooms, attending to light maintenance, doing mailings, and baking cookies. 
Some 50 volunteers come in to help as often as twice a week or as little as  twice a month. Most  family 
activities take place in the evenings or first thing in the morning. But often healthy brothers and sisters are 
in the House during the day. When there is a healthy sibling under age sixteen, there is usually a parent at 
the House also.<p>
  The House rules are mostly just common sense. Children must be supervised by an adult. Quiet time is 10 
p.m. to 7 a.m. Because there is no maid service, families have to pick up after themselves and their children 
in the common areas as well as in their private rooms. And of course, they must make sure that their 
children are courteous to others. No smoking is permitted inside, and no alcohol may be drunk anywhere 
on the premises. Food and drinks are allowed in the dining room and kitchen only, unless a child is 
bedridden. <p>
  Because the House, its staff, and the families seem so cheerful, reminders of the purpose of Ronald 
McDonald House can be slightly jarring. Reading through the House rules is reminder enough. Hand 
washing is taken very seriously here, as is proper disposal of diapers, syringes, and blood specimens. 
House managers must be notified if anyone in the House is exposed to contagious disease; chicken pox can 
be fatal to children with weakened immune systems. <p>
  One of the most remarkable things about Barbara and Debbie is their approach to illness and death
particularly  the deaths of children. Certainly there is grief, which is as much a part of death as death is a 
part of life. But they are both passionate and practical about what they do. They have no soapbox, and there 
is no melodrama as they talk to us about the often terrible suffering of the families and children they serve. <p>

<h3>Practical Services</h3>
<p>
  This practical but caring approach manifests itself in several other services the House provides. For 
instance, a former playroom was converted into a classroom in 1992. Because patients, as well as their 
healthy brothers and sisters, often had no way of keeping up with their schoolwork, Fiorella Carmelino, the 
tutorial coordinator, has recruited and trained about sixteen volunteer tutors. They assist  patients at the 
House, their sisters and brothers, children who are confined to the hospital, and indeed any child at 
Childrens Hospital who requests help. Tutors spend two to three hours per week working with students on 
a one-to-one basis, usually meeting with two or three students per session.<p>
  As the nations capital, Washington offers children educational opportunities that can compensate for 
what they are missing in their schools at home. Volunteers from local colleges and retiree organizations 
serve as tutors and  chaperones on field trips. Outings are organized to such places as the Smithsonians Air 
and Space Museum, the National Gallery, the Lincoln Memorial, the White House, the Capitol, and the 
National Zoo.<p>
  The House also provides for many  families that dont have transportation, especially those who are flown 
in from overseas.  Shuttle vans run four times a day  to any hospital where a child is treated, and to grocery 
stores and to a shopping mall on the weekend. Even those who do bring a car may find  the prospect of 
driving in a large, unfamiliar city daunting.<p>
  And to keep families in touch with friends and relatives, MCI and AT&T have donated special phones  
for brief long-distance calls every day. Regular phone service is also available, and three pay phones are on 
the premises. The House even provides pagers to parents whose children are in intensive care so that the 
hospital can reach them no matter where they are day or night.<p>

<h3>The House That Love Built</h3>
<p>
  The first Ronald McDonald House was the product of a quixotic partnership of an NFL franchise, a 
pediatric oncologist, and local McDonalds franchise owners (see sidebarpage 4). The concept grew out 
of a conversation between Fred Hill, a tight end for the Philadelphia Eagles, and Dr. Audrey Evans, one of 
the doctors treating Hills three-year-old daughter Kim for leukemia. The first house opened near 
Philadelphia Childrens Hospital in 1974.<p>
  Debbie describes their relationship with McDonalds as wonderfulboth in terms of manpower and on a 
volunteer level. If the House needs a van it may ask local franchise owners to  raise the money. 
McDonalds suppliers also help the Ronald McDonald House. The D.C. House, for instance, receives free 
dairy products from the Shenandoah Pride Dairy.<p>
  None of the Ronald McDonald Houses could exist solely on what McDonalds does for them. This is 
especially true for the larger Houses. The D.C. House, for instance, depends on the community for the 
overwhelming majority of its annual operating budget. It fluctuates yearly, but is now at just over 
$700,000.  McDonalds restaurant counter boxes are projected to account for just over 17% of the 1996 
budget.<p>
  Debbie, who has been executive director for seven years, is responsible for public relations, management 
and fund-raising. Her very active, forty member Board, composed of parents of children with cancer, 
doctors, social workers, McDonalds representatives, and community leaders, assists with management, 
finance, fund-raising and special events. Each board member must serve on at least one committee.<p>
  The House had no executive director from the time the House opened in 1980 until Debbie came on in 
1989.  The sole staff person, a resident manager, lived on the premises and the Board filled in as needed. 
Debbie now directs four full-time and four part-time staff members.<p>
  While the D.C. House participates in the Combined Federal Campaign, it does not receive any 
government money. In fact, its fund-raising relies almost exclusively on local projects designed to serve a 
dual purpose, raise the always-needed funds, and increase community awareness of the facility. Special 
events raise a  large portion of their budget. While always happy to accept money, the House also 
welcomes gifts in kind. Right now Debbie is looking for a van and a new plain paper fax machine.<p>
  If the Ronald McDonald House has an event planned Debbie tries to get it on the radio or in the 
newspaper. Often she will put out a call for volunteers to  adopt  parts of the garden, bake cookies, or rake 
the yard. She constantly reminds the community that the House depends upon volunteers every day from 
9:00 a.m. to 9:00 p.m.  This high profile approach helps to insure that the community knows that there is a 
Ronald McDonald House in the area that needs volunteers and money.<p>
  Recalling the role of the Philadelphia Eagles, the largest annual fund-raising event involves the 
Washington Redskins football team. The event, Rally Round the Redskins, was begun in the Houses  
first year of operation. It features a live and silent auction, dinner, and an autograph and photo session 
which the House holds with the Redskins each fall. The entire teamcoaches and playersis invited to 
greet anyone who might be interested in meeting  the players and supporting the House. <p>
  Each year there also is an annual golf tournament and four or five smaller events. These included wine 
tastings, raffles, and a dinner cruise. This March the House held its first annual Ultimate Hunt for the 
Good Egg. Eighty celebrity-decorated Easter Eggs, creations by the likes of by Elton John, Corretta Scott 
King, General Norman Schwartzkopf, President Ford and Bob and Elizabeth Dole were auctioned off. The 
event, cosponsored with Neiman Marcus, culminated in the presentation of the first annual Good Egg 
Award to Donna and Gilbert Giordano, keystone supporters of the House.
<h3>Giving Back</h3>
<p>
  The D.C. Ronald McDonald House asks that families who can afford it pay a $10 fee per daynicely 
splitting the difference between the high ($25) and low ($5) established by the Ronald McDonald House 
International Advisory Board. It is certainly not for the revenue, says Debbie. This may be a matter of 
opinion, but I believe the old saying that when people get something for nothing they sometimes dont 
value it, or they almost forget that it costs something for them to stay here. At least this small stipend helps 
families feel that they belong and that they are making a contribution or giving back.  Debbie and Barbara 
estimate that the fee is  waived for at least half of the families. <p>
  But the House, they are quick to remind us, runs on two things: one is money, the other is volunteer 
power. So they also ask all families to volunteer in the House. As with the fee, help is asked on an as 
youre able basis. Some families have many hours to volunteer, others dont. This often depends on how 
sick their child is and how much time theyre spending at the hospital. But most families are quite willing  
to do things for the common areas like take out the trash and change light bulbs.<p>
  Helping out also depends on how each individual deals with stress. Some people need to keep busy, 
others internalize their energy and become contemplative. One  father who was here during  the 
extraordinary blizzards in 1996 kept the walk clear. It was his way to relieve stress and help out. Barbara 
remembers another father whose child was not going to live. He mowed the lawn to relieve stress. The 
childs mother had to be at the hospital; he had to leave. He had to mow the lawn. Thats how he dealt with 
it. For many guests, being able to pull a weed in the garden not only makes them feel more at home, it is a 
necessary pressure valve.<p>
  Currently Debbie and board members are busy supervising the building of another Ronald McDonald 
House on the grounds of Fairfax Hospital in Virginia. It will be an eight bedroom facility to better serve 
hospitals in the Northern Virginia area. Having received the go-ahead, they have selected the design of the 
House and have found builders. They have a lease in hand, and if all goes well the groundbreaking will be 
in August or September.<p> 
  Meanwhile, they also are expanding the House in northeast D.C. The Board of Zoning has approved a 
manufactured three-bedroom housing unit to house three additional bone marrow transplant families, 
whose children need an even greater levels of isolation because of  their weakened immune systems.
<p>
<hr>
<p>
  As rising medical costs threaten families whose children require treatment over a long period, clearly the 
Ronald McDonald House provides a helpful safety net. Parents may miss work and have trouble meeting 
uninsured  costs.  But at the Ronald McDonald House they at least will have food and shelter for little or no 
cost.<p>
  Yet the House serves an even more important function. At a time when a familys emotional stability is at 
risk and when financial and personal tensions may be high, Ronald McDonald House keeps the family 
together. Painful decisions about who has to stay behind are avoided because the House keeps parents close 
to their hospitalized child. It relieves the necessity of long and frequent drives to the hospital when a child 
is in pain or queasy from treatment. And it allows family members to remain charitable to one another 
under the weight of stress and exhaustion. When families are spending day after day with a loved one at the 
hospital, it is hard to overestimate the healing power of a warm shower, a comfortable bed, and a meal that 
didnt come from the hospital cafeteria.
<p>
<h3>The First Ronald McDonald House</h3><p>
  When Fred Hill, tight end for the Philadelphia Eagles, asked Dr. Audrey Evans, head of the pediatric 
oncology unit at Childrens Hospital of Philadelphia, how he could help the families she was working with, 
neither expected her answer to that question to grow into a household name. <p>
  What Dr. Evans wanted was a house that could serve as a temporary residence for the families of children  
treated at her hospital. She caught Hill at his most receptive. Ever since his daughter Kim had been 
diagnosed with leukemia, Hill and his wife had camped out on hospital chairs and benches, eating food 
from vending machines, and doing all they could to keep Kim from seeing their fear, exhaustion, and 
frustration.<p>
  All around them, other parents were doing exactly the same thing. Many of the families had traveled great 
distances to bring their children to the hospital, but the high cost of hotel rooms was more than they could 
afford. Hill was convinced that Dr. Evans idea for a home-away-from-home for families of seriously ill 
children was exactly what was needed. <p>
  Hill rallied his teammates. Through the Philadelphia Eagles general manager, Jim Murray, the whole 
team offered its support. While Dr. Evans looked for real estate around the hospital, Murray called on his 
friends at McDonalds, who were planning a St. Patricks Day Shamrock Shake promotion. On requesting 
a portion of the proceeds, Murray was told by the local McDonalds that the project could have them all.<p>
  The Shamrock Shake promotion raised some $35,000, almost enough to cover the $40,000 purchase price 
of a four-story, seven-bedroom house that Dr. Evans found near the hospital. The interior required 
extensive renovation to convert it from a student rooming house into a temporary home for kids and their 
families. With help from a local developer whose own daughter had been diagnosed with leukemia, the 
house was gutted, rebuilt, furnished, and opened in October of 1974. <p>
  When it came time to name the house, they decided on the Ronald McDonald House in gratitude to the 
local franchise owners who had helped so generously, and because it was hoped that it would be 
comforting for a hospitalized child to know that his parents would be staying at Ronalds House.<p>
  Within a year, word had spread and Eagles General Manager Jim Murray went to Chicago to help 
Childrens Memorial Hospital and several area residents establish a Ronald McDonald House there. Again, 
a milkshake promotion supported by local McDonalds and their customers provided the fundraising 
centerpiece. The second Ronald McDonald House opened in Chicago in April of 1977. <p>
  By 1979, 10 more Ronald McDonald Houses had opened. In the next five years, local communities 
founded 60 more Houses; then 53 more in the following five years. Today, there are 164 Ronald 
McDonald Houses in 13 countries. <p>
  <b>Kim Hill, the little girl whose illness started it all, is now a mother in California. And Jim Murray, the 
Eagles general manager who helped found the first and many subsequent Ronald McDonald Houses, now 
serves as president of the Ronald McDonald House International Advisory Board.</b>
<p>
<a href="#top">Return to Top</a><p>
<a name="name"><i>Gwen Purtill is  managing editor of Crisis Magazine. Pat Purtill is development director 
for the National Council for Adoption.  </i></a>
