<I><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Times New Roman"><h2>Foundation Watch</h2><p>
</FONT></I><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Times New Roman">April 1996</font>

<P>
<a href="#ed">From the Editor</i>
<br><a href="#in">In the Best Interests of the Child
</a>
<br><a href="#targeted">Targeted Giving to "Fight the Right"
</a>
<br><a href="#pro">Pro-Family, Pro-Choice
</a>
<br><a href="#our">Our Bodies, Our Selves
</a>
<br><a href="#a">A Committment to the Arts</a>
<br>
<a href="#robert">Robert Sterling Clark Foundations Clubbable Board of Dir.
</a>
<br><a href="#">Anti Catholic Opposition Research
</a>
<br>
<a href="#foundation">Foundation Watch Study: Media Payouts</a><br>
<a href="#letters">Letters</a><br>
<a href="#cor">Correction</a><br>
<a href="#table">Table of Contents</a><p>
<a name="ed"></a>
<b>From The Editor:</b>
<P>
Right now, courts are supervising the child foster care programs in some 21 states.  In the 
District of Columbia, a federal court judge has stripped mayor Marion Barry of control 
over child welfare and replaced the elected city administration with a court-appointed 
consultant.  The judge described the "outrageous deficiencies" in D.C.'s child foster care 
in a March 17th, 1996 news story headlined "A Dickensian Picture" and reported on the 
front page of the Sunday New York Times.<p>
	What readers of the article did not learn from reporter Robert Pear was that almost 
twenty years ago the Robert Sterling Clark Foundation, a private grantmaking 
philanthropy in New York City with current assets estimated at $90 million, laid the 
foundations for what has become the legal struggle to use the courts to revamp the child 
welfare system. <p>
	Led by its energetic and articulate executive director, Margaret C. Ayers, the 
Robert Sterling Clark Foundation is the story behind the re-orientation of the nation's 
thinking on child welfare.  Ayers is admirable for her forthrightness and willingness to 
clarify her views.  She spoke at length with Foundation Watch.  But the opinions she 
expresses and the goals for which she fights reveal the inherent limitations in her liberal 
though anti-bureaucratic stance:  She truly believes the paradoxical slogan "Pro-family, 
pro-choice."<p>
	Though it has funded the legal challenge to failing government child protection 
services, the Robert Sterling Clark Foundation also funds those who support state action 
for abortion rights while attacking the rights of religious groups to establish childcare 
arrangements when parents are absent or unfit.<p>
	Sympathetic government bureaucrats, like Br'er Rabbitt, have often appreciated 
the adverse publicity and legal briar patches into which they are tossed by the Robert 
Sterling Clark Foundation.  Seeming to be opponents, government and its philanthropic 
adversaries have been, in fact, complicit in attempts to expand the power of the state over 
childcare and reduce the influence of independent institutions such as the Catholic 
Church.  <p>
	Although once dubbed a "government accountability project," the Foundation has 
succeeded in removing child welfare programs from the direct supervision of government 
officials who are accountable to the electorate.  Instead, a cadre of professional 
criminologists, sociologists, psychologists, educators and social workers has been 
empowered by the judicial process.  And while it opposes the theories of so-called 
"family preservation," much favored by some prominent child welfare advocacy groups, 
the Robert Sterling Clark Foundation has funded those who would use the courts to 
establish alternative therapeutic regimes for the care of children.<p>
	Perplexingly, the Foundation's advocacy of child welfare derives from Margaret 
Ayers' feminism, which champions women's right to abortion and other so-called 
reproductive rights.  This is the second major funding priority of the Robert Sterling 
Clark Foundation.  The third is increased funding for cultural institutions and the arts.  In 
the past year, Ayers has capped these interests by announcing to the press her 
determination to resist those who are in opposition to the goals she supports.  She has 
organized this effort under the banner, "Fight the Right." <p>

<a href="#table">Table of Contents</a><p>
<a name="in"></a>
<b>IN THE BEST INTERESTS OF THE CHILD</b><p>

The executive director of the Robert Sterling Clark Foundation has spent a good part of her professional life working to reform the child welfare system.  In the 1960's Ayers spent four years as a New York City social worker who witnessed firsthand the abuse and suffering of children at the hands of an unresponsive bureaucracy.  She left the system after New York City's Commissioner of Welfare banned home visits by social workers in 1968, claiming that they constituted an invasion of privacy and an undesirable form of espionage.  (Ayers does not say this was the reason).  But she did not forget what she had seen nor the benefit of the home visits.<p>
	Ayers told Foundation Watch:  "Mitch Ginsberg [then-New York City welfare commissioner now deceased] separated income maintenance from services.  But the fact is that my colleagues and I were really social workers.  We were not there investigating clients.  We were there trying to help clients; help them get off welfare, substance abuse.  
When income maintenance was separated, the social work staff was reduced.  And the city hired paper pushers who did not provide services.  The caseworkers of the late 60s were not watchdogs.  We were trying to help welfare recipients get into programs that would enable them to lead constructive lives." <p>
	Following her stint in social work, and in a program associate position at the Edna McConnell Clark Foundation (no relation, assets $525 million), Ayers came to Robert Sterling Clark as a consultant in 1976.  She found a small private foundation which gave out grants in an unfocused manner in many areas. <p>
	The Robert Sterling Clark Foundation was incorporated in 1952  to shelter and distribute a portion of the inheritance derived from the Singer sewing machine fortune.  Founder Robert Sterling Clark was the grandson of Edward Clark, a lawyer who founded the Singer company with Isaac Singer in the nineteenth century.  Last year, with a smaller 
$70 million fund, the Foundation gave away about $3.5 million.  A small operation with a staff of five, its giving reflects Ayers' intense personal commitment and leadership.<p>
	Says Ayers:  "The board hired me to look at what they'd been doing and try to figure out what fields it made sense to be in.  At that point the foundation was giving grants in ten fields.  There were lots of small grants in science, health, population, environment, education.  It wasn't a developed grants program.  It wasn't focused beyond 
broad categories.  Some areas were sufficiently broad as to render our grantmaking ineffective."<p>
	Ayers proposed to concentrate Clark's grants in three major areas: child welfare reform, monitoring the performance of government agencies in delivering services, and support for cultural institutions and the arts.  Since then, the Foundation has combined the first two fields, kept support for the arts, and added a third area: "insuring access to reproductive health information and services," which paid out grants totalling $1,406,000 in 1994 (information for 1995 is not yet available).  The largest single grant _ $200,000 _ 
went to The Planned Parenthood Federation of America to conduct research on pro-life activists.  By comparison, projects to improve public institutions in New York City and State were funded at the level of $1,084,000. The Foundation funded the arts and cultural institutions with grants totalling $1,196,080.<p>
	Ayers' concern for child welfare was an aspect of the Foundation's "government 
accountability" project begun in 1979 during the administration of New York City mayor 
Ed Koch. That effort focused on the city's administrative failings in responding to child 
abuse and neglect.<p>
	The Foundation made grants to the New York Civil Liberties Union to support litigation against the city.  In particular, from 1979 to 1994 it earmarked annual grants (excepting 1980 and 1988) to children's rights advocate Marcia Robinson Lowry.  She had come to fame as an attorney in a 1973 case, Wilder v. Bernstein, which forced New York City to end the use of religious criteria in making foster placements of children to Catholic and other religious homes.  In a consent decree, the city agreed that such placements violated constitutional guarantees of separation between church and state.<p>
	Since its first grant in 1979, the Robert Sterling Clark Foundation has given over 
$900,000 to the ACLU's children's rights project, which was headed until last year by Lowry.  In 1994 the foundation gave Lowry's project $80,000.  Last year Lowry left the ACLU to establish her own nonprofit, Children's Rights, Inc., with $90,000 in foundation support from Ayers.  At the ACLU Lowry enjoyed considerable success litigating child 
welfare and adoption cases, including the D.C. case which ended the Barry administration's authority over child protection services.  The essential role of the Robert Sterling Clark Foundation in making those successes possible has received little public 
attention.<p>
	Stanley Brezenoff, who was responsible for child welfare enforcement as first deputy mayor in the Koch administration, says, "The unique thing about Peggy Ayers is that she and the Robert Sterling Clark Foundation don't shrink from cutting edge issues.  <p>
We wouldn't have redoubled our effort to improve such a massive system, so unrelenting, such an enormous system, with thousands of reports of abuse and neglect, without the advocacy and prodding which came from the children's rights project.  We needed to be pushed and prodded.  The ACLU has come down on both sides.  It's not a liberal or conservative issue.  I admire Peggy and that foundation tremendously for what they've done."<p>
	Unfortunately, says Ayers, "A lot of the good we did, came undone," when David Dinkins replaced Koch as New York City's mayor.  Claiming ongoing city neglect of child welfare, Lowry's Children's Rights project at the ACLU filed the lawsuit Marisol A. <p>
v. Giuliani which is currently before U.S. District Judge Robert Ward in New York.  (The case, televised on Court TV, will also set precedent regarding the presence of cameras in a federal courtroom.)<p>

<a href="#table">Table of Contents</a><p>
<a name="targeted"></a>
<b>TARGETED GIVING TO "FIGHT THE RIGHT"</b><p>

Passionate" is the word often used by those who know Ayers, executive director of the Robert Sterling Clark Foundation since 1979.  She uses the word herself: "I feel passionately about our work, the work of the foundation." In a universe known for an addiction to euphemism and dissimulation, what Dwight 
MacDonald called the "foundation-speak" of the "philanthropoids," Ayers is a refreshingly straight shooter.<p>
	Ayers is a shrewd politician whose views are respected by others in the world of organized philanthropy.  And she has a reputation as a "hands on" donor:  Ayers not only consults with the CEOs and development officers of the groups she funds, but she works directly with the staff members who run the programs that her grants support.<p>
	In many ways Margaret Ayers is the Robert Sterling Clark Foundation.  A tall handsome brunette in her mid-fifties, Ayers lives in Manhattan in the fashionable East-60's, maintains a country house upstate and is known as a conservative dresser who 
favors Chanel-like suits.  Ayers' annual salary is $150,000, with $22,387 additional in benefits. <p>
	Yet in September, 1995 Ayers told the Chronicle of Philanthropy that her mission 
as head of the Robert Sterling Clark Foundation is to "fight the right."  The battle began, she said, with the election of Ronald Reagan in 1980.  Ayers says she concluded then that the most important threat to women's rights came from the White House and the Republican party.  Observing the appointment of conservative movement activists and religious conservatives to Executive Branch agencies, Ayers persuaded her board that the Foundation should initiate a grants program to support abortion rights.<p>
	In this regard, Robert Sterling Clark has made some extraordinary grants.  For instance, it has paid recipient organizations to engage in "opposition research."  Some 1994 grant projects include:<br><ul>
	<li>  $80,000 to the National Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action League for a 
computer database tracking abortion legislation, court cases, and publication of Sexuality 
In America: A State-By-State Review. 
	<li>  $60,000 to Catholics For Free Choice for A New Rite, a published database 
compiling information on conservative Catholic organizations and individuals.
	<li>  $40,000 to the Feminist Majority Foundation for investigations of pro-life 
groups.
	<li>  $200,000 over two years to Planned Parenthood for "clinic defense strategies" 
and a database of abortion opponents. 
	<li>  $80,000 to People for the American Way for its "Artsave" database of 
controversial art and for publication of Artistic Freedom Under Attack.  
	<li>  $50,000 to the ACLU's "Arts Censorship Project" to represent artists and arts 
organizations that "are under attack by government and private-pressure groups for 
creating and exhibiting works of art that deal with sexual or controversial themes."</ul>
	
	Despite its small size, the Robert Sterling Clark Foundation exerts considerable influence over nationwide abortion rights grantmaking.  Ayers heads the Council on Foundations' official Reproductive Rights Affinity Group, "Grantmakers in Support of 
Reproductive Rights."  <p>
	Formed in 1990 at Ayers' urging in light of the restrictions on abortion contained 
in the Supreme Court's decision in Webster v. Reproductive Health Services, the group 
has 80 grantmaker members who "encourage foundations to give more money to organizations that advocate broad access to abortion and birth control." <p>
	The group succeeded a smaller, more secretive and unofficial team organized in 
1984.  Ayers told the Chronicle of Philanthropy in 1990 that one in four foundations 
invited to join the group did so because the decision had "shaken a lot of people to the 
roots."  <p>
	In 1991 Ayers called on the twenty largest foundations that fund abortion rights to 
meet at the Ford Foundation to plan a strategy in response to Rust v. Sullivan, the 
Supreme Court ruling that upheld the federal government's authority to prohibit federally-
funded clinic workers from recommending abortion.  <p>
	In 1993, the Robert Sterling Clark Foundation donated $100,000 to the Center for 
Reproductive Law and Policy, when the pro-abortion group split from the ACLU.  <p>
	The New York Times reported that the new group was meant to attract 
Republicans such as Barbara Mosbacher, co-chairman of the New York State Republican 
Family Comittee and Republican Pro-Choice Political Action Committee, who opposed 
other ACLU positions. <p>
	 "Some people are incensed by some of the ACLU's stances," she told the Times.  
Nat Hentoff, a pro-life member of the ACLU board of directors responded, "It's good for 
the ACLU that this close identification gets  less close."<p>

<a href="#table">Table of Contents</a><p>
<a name="pro"></a>
<b>"PRO-FAMILY, PRO-CHOICE": FROM WOMEN'S RIGHTS TO CHILDREN'S RIGHTS</b><p>

As Ayers supported improving the lives of children, she also strengthened her commitment to the pro-abortion cause.  She sees no conflict and offers the argument:  "It is critical to the ability of women to be integral parts 
of our economic system for them to have control over their reproductive lives.  I don't 
want the government telling me what to do in my bedroom.  I don't want the church 
telling me what to do in my bedroom.  I don't want them controlling what I do."<p> 
	During pregnancy, Ayers believes that the rights of the mother are paramount.  
The tables turn at birth.  "The life of the child begins at birth," she declared.  Only in this 
way can one understand the zeal with which the Robert Sterling Clark Foundation 
campaigns to remove children from abusive parents and abusive government programs, 
while funding those who would make it easier for mothers to terminate their pregnancies.<p>
	Ayers' four years in New York's slums and projects apparently have convinced her 
that it is better that some children not be born; but once born, children deserve quick 
removal from bad homes.  Ayers is a strong opponent of "family preservation," a social 
welfare concept embodied in a 1980 law which requires social workers to keep families 
together for as long as possible and balance this requirement against others. Ayers, 
however, favors early removal of abused children "in the best interests of the child."<p> 
	In this, Ayers rejects the position of some of the most prominent and well-
connected children's rights advocates, the Child Welfare League of America, the 
Children's Defense Fund (CDF), and First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, its former chair. 
In her new book, It Takes A Village (Simon and Schuster, 1996, reviewed in Capital 
Research Center's Alternatives In Philanthropy March, 1996), the First Lady tries to have 
it both ways, defending the priority of the "best interests of the child" while 
simultaneously arguing for family preservation efforts. "It is not only parents who need 
expert 'coaching' in children's development," she writes. "The rest of the village does 
too."  <p>
	The Robert Sterling Clark Foundation stopped funding the Children's Defense 
Fund in the late 1980's because, according to Ayers, "CDF was not conducting work that 
qualified it to receive funds under any of our programs." It was shortly after Ayers 
discontinued the national child welfare program she had established upon her arrival.  
Although Ayers will not criticize the First Lady or CDF, it should be noted that the 
foundation continued to fund other child welfare projects through its New York-centered 
"government accountability" efforts _ but it still does not fund CDF or its local "New 
York City Child Health Project" (with offices at 111 Broadway in Manhattan). Ayers also 
differs with CDF's refusal to fight against race-based placement for adopted children.  
Indeed, some consider Children's Rights Inc. to be a new competitor to CDF's base of 
philanthropic support.<p>
	Yet, despite her differences with the conventional wisdom of the child welfare 
establishment, some experts don't find that Ayers's position offers much of an alternative.  
Douglas Besharov of the American Enterprise Institute remarks that more money, more 
social workers, and more court supervision of child welfare programs have had no 
positive long term impact on the child welfare system.  <p>
	"My basic thought is that courts can't reform child welfare agencies." he says.  
"Real reform needs the will of the community. The track record of spending more money 
is there, hiring more caseworkers is there, and it doesn't necessarily improve services to 
children because judges and lawyers can't run social service agencies."<p>
	More critical is William Donohue, a sociologist who is president of the Catholic 
League for Religious and Civil Rights in New York City.  He accuses attorney Marcia 
Lowry of attempting to destroy the Catholic child welfare agencies when she filed the 
1973 Wilder v. Bernstein suit (that found payments to religious agencies for foster care 
and adoption in violation of the Constitution's guarantee of separation of church and 
state).  Donohue calls Lowry "anti-Catholic" (though Lowry denies it) and predicts that 
child welfare systems under court monitors will suffer the same legal problems as mental 
hospitals which have been forced to deinstitutionalize patients, prisons which have been 
under court order to release criminals, and school systems which have been ordered by 
courts to raise property taxes to pay for new buildings and more teachers in vain attempts 
to improve student achievement and stop white flight. <p>
	The goal of Children's Rights Inc. lawsuits, says Donohue, is not to improve 
children's lives, but instead to concentrate power in court-appointed monitors who are 
approved by ACLU lawyers like Lowry.  The suits themselves cost millions of dollars 
which are drained from child welfare budgets into the pockets of lawyers and consultants.  
And the result is that accountability is removed from an electorate which has very 
different religious and moral values.<p>
	"The New York foster-care issue represents a fair characterization of the atomistic 
view of liberty," writes Donohue in his critical analysis of the ACLU, The Twilight of 
Liberty (Transaction, 1994).  "According to this perspective, freedom from religion is 
valued more highly than religious liberty, and that is why state encroachment on religious 
institutions is not interpreted as a threat.  If anything, the atomistic view holds that the 
prospects of liberty are advanced by weakening the influence of religiously-sponsored 
institutions."<p>
	Ayers disagrees that religious liberty is endangered when courts take over child 
welfare, arguing that "litigation is the only certain method of shedding light on child 
welfare systems that hide behind confidentiality laws."<p>
	On the other hand, Richard Gelles, a professor of sociology at the University of 
Rhode Island and author The Book of David: How Preserving Families Can Cost 
Children's Lives (Basic Books, 1996), argues that lawsuits such as Lowry's are inevitable 
but entirely off the mark.  The badly-drafted 1980 federal law which is the basis for court 
filings requires cities and states to pursue mutually contradictory policies: family 
preservation and the best interests of the child.  Because it is impossible to do both, 
lawsuits are inescapable.  Yet they will accomplish nothing.  Gelles argues that the only 
criterion should be the best interests of the child. <p>
	"Connecticut had children dying left and right under a consent decree," Gelles 
told Foundation Watch.  "The decree didn't order them to do the right thing.  You can't 
balance family preservation and child safety." <p>
	And Elizabeth Bartholet, a professor of Family Law at Harvard University 
concurs:  "I think family preservation is part of the problem today.  There is an 
overwhelming bias in our laws and funding priorities for family preservation that is 
inconsistent with the best interests of children."<p>
	In this, Bartholet and Gelles agree with Margaret Ayers, who told Foundation 
Watch, "I've been an observer of the child welfare system for thirty years, and I don't 
think there are any studies which show that family preservation works." 	<p>
	But, says Gelles,  "Lowry believes more social workers, more training, more 
intervention can solve the problem.  They can't.  Until the law is changed, things can't 
improve for children." Yet Ayers disagrees about the root problem, claiming "it is not the 
law. The fault lies in its implementation."<p>
	Gelles responds, "You cannot implement a vague, ambiguous, and inherently 
contradictory law. If you change 'reasonable efforts' to 'child safety' then you hold the 
states accountable."<p>
	In the debate over adoption and foster care, Ayers drops ideological arguments 
and partisan rhetoric.  She says, "I hesitate to say whether it is a conservative or liberal 
position. Basically I'm concerned about the well-being of children in a very vulnerable 
situation."<p>
	In this area Ayers seems to have adopted the self-reflexive and self-critical 
position of Naomi Wolf, who wrote in The New Republic, "the best understanding of 
feminism involves holding women as well as men to the responsibilities that are 
inseparable from their rights."<p>

<a href="#table">Table of Contents</a><p>
<a name="our"></a>
<b>OUR BODIES, OUR SELVES</b><p>

About abortion, however, there 	are no doubts.  In giving grants 	to groups monitoring the politics of the abortion issue, Ayers has put the 
Robert Sterling Clark Foundation firmly on the side of those who regard abortion as 
central to women's liberation.<p>
	Ayers, who never married, is a truly liberated woman. She says she is not 
primarily interested in abortion for "population control" or "environmental" reasons, the 
argument made by some in the philanthropic community.  Instead, she says the right of a 
woman to control her own body is fundamental to a woman's freedom from oppression.  
The ability to terminate a pregnancy at will must be a premise of individual freedom and 
women's liberation.  This outlook has its roots in the feminism of the 1970's and it 
informs her thinking and her grantmaking. <p>
	"We spend a lot of time trying to promote women's access to reproductive health 
care.  And we have abstinence, but that's where conservative groups end the discussion.  
Many of these groups are not supportive of abortion, not supportive of family planning, 
not supportive of sexuality education," says Ayers.<p>
	The Reagan administration agenda was diametrically opposed to hers, she notes.  
"In 1983-84 there was an edict that came out of the Office of Management and Budget 
that all grantmaking agencies had to examine the projects they were supporting and the 
organizations they were giving grants to insure the purposes of the organizations and 
projects were consonant with White House policies."  Ayers refers to an ACLU legal 
challenge that led to the reinstatement of a USAID grant to the Alan Guttmacher Institute.  
She also mentions Department of Health and Human Service regulations on health clinics 
that separated family planning from abortion and the Rust "gag rule"decision. <p>
	In response, the Robert Sterling Clark Foundation made abortion the battleground 
of feminism.  Its fight continues.  Besides the previously cited opposition research  
funding, the Foundation made the following grants in 1994:<br><ul>
	<li>  $75,000 to the New York Civil Liberties Union to pay for "litigation 
challenging the exclusion of abortion services from New York's expanded Mediaid 
program." 
	<li>  $50,000 to Planned Parenthood of Metropolitan Washington for "coalition 
building and grassroots organizing and the development of a database of information on 
the theocratic right and its tactics." 
	<li>  $60,000 to the Ms. Foundation for Women for the "Reproductive Rights 
Coalition Fund." 
	<li>  $50,000 to the NOW Legal Defense and education Fund to "secure legal 
protection for abortion providers." 
	<li>  $60,000 to the National Abortion Federation for "the creation of a Legal 
Clearinghouse" to "combat clinic harrassment." 
	<li>  $200,000 over two years to Advocates For Youth (formerly the Center for 
Population Options) which provides sex education to teenagers. 
	<li>  $40,000 to the Center for Policy Alternatives for a "Support Network for 
Pro-Choice Leaders." 
	<li>	$30,000 to the Center for Reproductive Law and Policy FAIR Health Care 
Reform Project to advocate the inclusion of abortion in health care;
	<li>	$75,000 to the Communications Consortium, for the "Reproductive Health 
Media Strategies Project," whose goal is "achieving better press coverage from the 
pro-choice perspective." 	
	<li>	$55,000 to the National Family Planning and Reproductive Health 
Association to "redress health reform measures that threaten access to reproductive health 
care." 
	<li>	$60,000 to the National Women's Law Center, to "support the Center's 
reproductive rights work." 
	<li>	$41,200 to the ProChoice Resource Center of Mamaroneck, NY to 
"monitor voter identification projects." 
	<li>	$50,000 to the Religious Coalition for Reproductive Choice, to 
"strengthen its Clergy Network. . .and raise the visibility of the pro-choice religious 
position." 
	<li>  $120,000 over two years to the Sex Information and Education Council of the 
US for "the expansion of the National Coalition to Support Sexuality Education.
	<li>  $60,000 to the Women's Legal Defense Fund for the "National Pro-Choice 
Coalition."</ul>
	Paradoxically, the success of the pro-abortion movement reduces the number of 
babies available for adoption by loving couples unable to have children _the clear goal of 
Robert Sterling Clark's children's rights efforts, which gets only a fraction of the 
Foundation's abortion funding. <p>

<a href="#table">Table of Contents</a><p>
<a name="a"></a>
<b>A COMMITMENT TO THE ARTS</b>
<p>

Ayers justifies the Foundation's 
		commitment to the arts as in 
		keeping with the personal interests of Robert Sterling Clark, a collector 
who established the Sterling and Francine Clark Art Institute in Williamstown, 
Massachusetts.  But in an unusual move, Ayers has focused her giving on administrative 
and infrastructure projects as well as on proposals purporting to defend free expression.<p>
	Like its schizophrenic policy of children's rights and abortion rights, the Robert 
Sterling Clark Foundation has a Janus-faced view of support for the arts.  It funds both 
business ventures to help generate revenues for arts organizations which conservatives 
would find easy to support,  as well as People for the American Way's "Artsave" project, 
which compiles charges of so-called "censorship" -- which often are just complaints from 
outraged citizens.<p>
	On the other hand, Ayers is very proud of the Robert Sterling Clark Foundation's 
support for income generating projects in the arts.  Among the most successful of these 
was a grant underwriting the scene shop of Playwrights Horizons, a small theatre 
workshop in New York City.  Once headed by Andre Bishop, now artistic director of the 
Lincoln Center theatre company, and Paul Daniels, Playwrights Horizons established 
"Scenic Central," a cooperative storage and construction facility which employed 
non-union labor to build sets for nonprofit theatre companies along New York's 42nd 
Street Theatre Row.  This enterprise created "a million dollar cashflow for the theatre 
company," says Ayers.<p>
	Andre Bishop told Foundation Watch that the scene shop "helped our whole 
theatre world. It grew to be pretty big, and was a way of achieving self-motivated 
financial independence."  Bishop added that "of all the funding sources, Peggy is the most 
knowledgable and sympathetic, very into improving business practices."  Besides "Scenic 
Central," Bishop says Ayers approved grants for new computer systems, audience 
devleopment, and other infrastructure programs.<p>
	However, the flip side of Ayers' union-busting entrepreneurship on Theatre Row 
is her support, on First Amendment grounds, for the most indefensible projects the 
National Endowment for the Arts has to offer.<p>
	By paying for legal defense teams, the Robert Sterling Clark Foundation helps 
insure that the NEA will remain unresponsive to taxpayers and their representatives. They 
approach arts controversies over Mapplethorpe, et. al. as free speech issues rather than 
issues of government accountability _ as the Foundation does over child welfare _ or of 
financial accountability _ as the Foundation does with its other arts grants.  This course 
will doom the NEA.  It caused Congress' two percent cut in the NEA's annual 
appropriations in 1992, then a five percent cut in 1994, a forty percent reduction last year, 
and now NEA's planned termination. For Congress must account for expenditures of tax 
dollars.<p>
	Foundation grants helped pay for  ACLU lawyers who represented the Cincinnati 
Museum of Art and director Dennis Barrie for an exhibition of works by Robert 
Mapplethorpe. They also represented so-called "NEA Four" performance artists.  The 
ACLU won the Mapplethorpe obscenity case, and it settled the grant denials litigation 
with Karen Finley, Tim Miller, Holly Hughes, and John Fleck (now a supporting cast 
member on NBC's Homicide) for a quarter of a million dollars.<p>
	By treating government arts funding as a First Amendment issue, Ayers has 
adopted the same "rights-based" arguments which she has used in fighting the abortion 
issue and that have become the essence of modern liberalism.  In 1994 Foundation grants 
defending the sanctity of the presumed "right" to offend the taxpayer have been made in 
the amounts of $50,000 to the National Campaign for Freedom of Expression, $50,000 to 
the National Cultural Alliance, $50,000 to the ACLU Arts Censorship Project, $25,000 to 
the Alliance for the Arts, and $80,000 to People for the American Way's Artsave Project.<p>
	Ayers fails to see the link between her funding and the NEA controversy, 
however, saying that "the Artsave project didn't really have anything to do with the NEA.  
The purpose was to make people aware of where people were being censored."  One 
suspects that the NEA is now expendable to arts advocates --  if its sacrifice on the altar 
of the First Amendment enables artists to continue to enjoy the myth of  their own 
rebellion.  It would be better if the Foundation concentrated on showing artists how to 
create markets for their work, attract audiences, and continue improving arts 
administration.<p>
	As in much of life, it seems as though the law of unintended consequences has 
directed the activities of the Robert Sterling Clark Foundation and its executive director.  
Despite its civil libertarian self-image, the Foundation has moved the arts into the 
marketplace.  And despite its aggressive advocacy of state-sanctioned abortion, it has 
highlighted the need to defend children from state welfare agencies and misguided 
"family preservation" policies.  In a sense, the Foundation is at a crossroads.  <p>
	For if Margaret Ayers would realize the good that the Robert Sterling Clark 
Foundation has done unintentionally, she might be able to re-orient her grants to match 
her empirical successes.  Ayers might fund maternity homes and orphanages instead of 
abortion clinics, religious instruction and etiquette classes instead of sexuality education, 
and concentrate on generating new profits and audiences for arts institutions and artists.<p>

<a href="#table">Table of Contents</a><p>
<a name="robert"></a>
<b>Robert Sterling Clark Foundations Clubbable<br> Board of Directors</b><p>

	The trustees of the Robert Sterling Clark Foundation have been described by 
those who know them as white shoe, Wall Street, and fiscally conservative.  One 
Ayers friend called them the kind of people [who], if you wanted to join a country club, 
you wouldnt want them to judge your application.  Yet Peggys got them buying 
condoms for high school kids.  Shes brought them around to positions they wouldnt 
ordinarily take.<p>
	The descriptions are entirely accurate.  If there is a Liberal Establishment, the 
Robert Sterling Clark board provides a good sampling of its members worthy of case 
study.<p>
	Winthrop R. Munyan, chairman of the board, is a prominent New York lawyer 
with offices on both Park and Lexington Avenues.  Director Raymond D. Horton heads 
New York Citys Citizens Budget Committee and boasts to reporters of receiving 
personal phone calls from former Governor Mario Cuomo while on vacation in Jamaica.  
Philip Svigals lives in fashionable Upper Montclair, New Jersey.<p> 
	Richardson Pratt, Jr., Williams class of 1946 and Harvard Business School, 
1948, is a resident of Cold Spring Harbor, Long Island, and a trustee of the Federation of 
Protestant Welfare Agencies, Near East Foundation, Brooklyn Botanical Garden, and 
Brooklyn Museum.  He is former chairman of Charles Pratt & Company, a director of the 
Dime Savings Bank of New York, and is now president of the Pratt Institute, a venerable 
art and engineering school in Brooklyn.<p>
	Miner Dunham Crary, Jr., Amherst class of 1942 and Harvard Law, 1948, is a 
Park Avenue lawyer with Crutis Mallet-Prevost, Colt & Mosle.  A member of the Union 
League, Century, and Huntington Country Clubs, he is a trustee of the American 
University in Cairo, the Hecksher Art Museum in Huntington, Long Island, the Sterling 
and Francine Clark Art Institute, and former chairman of the Amherst College alumni 
council executive committee. <p>
	John Niebrugge Romans, Williams, 1964, and Columbia Law, 1967, is also a 
partner at Curtis, Mallet-Prevost, Colt & Mosle and chairman of the Bar of the City of 
New Yorks Aeronautical Committee.  He is a member of the Princeton and the 
Larchmont Yacht Clubs.<p>
	John Hoyt Stookey, Amherst, 1952, and Columbia, 1955, is the most recent 
director.  He is chairman of Quantum Chemical Corporation (formerly National Distillers 
and Chemical Corporation), director of Riegel Textile Corporation and Rexham 
Corporation, founder of the Berkshire Boys Choir, the Canterbury Choral Society, former 
chairman of the health manpower committee of the United Hospital Fund, director of the 
Association for a Better New York, and a trustee of the Boston Symphony and 
Northfield-Mt. Hermon School.<p>
	The lone woman, Joanna DeHaven Underwood, Bryn Mawr, 1962 and 
Sorbonne, 1965, is executive director of INFORM, Inc., a public policy think-tank.  A 
former Time magazine reporter and former director of the Council on Economic 
Priorities, Underwood is on the board of directors of national Planned Parenthood and the 
New York State Energy Research and Development Authority.  She is a member of the 
U.S. Association for the Club of Rome and sits with David Rockefeller, Jr. and Gilbert 
Grosvenor, among others, on the Presidents Environmental Challenge Awards selection 
committee.<p>

<a href="#table">Table of Contents</a><p>
<a name="anti"></a>
<b>Anti Catholic Opposition Research</b><p>

	 A New Rite: Conservative Catholic Organizations And Their Allies, researched 
and written by Steve Askin,  was first published by Catholics For Free Choice in 1994 
and has been updated in 1995.<p>
	Except for its putative liberal tilt, the document reads like a Ku Klux Klan tract 
from the 1920's, complete with allegations of a Papist conspiracy active in America.  But 
this time, the charge is that the Church supports the Religious Right. Rather than 
advocating lynching, the author merely compiles an enemies list.<p>
	In compiling this directory, we attempted to identify the Catholic organizations -
- and their close collaborators -- whose agendas support this conservative blueprint for 
family and society says Askin.<p>
	Some of the organizations singled out for scrutiny include the Knights of Malta, 
the Knights of Columbus, and the Domino's Foundation (based on the pizza fortune).<p>
	The shrill tone plays to traditional anti-Catholic bigotry by scapegoating Catholics 
even for the activities of Baptists.<p>
	"It was a Catholic...Paul Weyrich... who concocted the phrase 'moral majority' 
and who designed the agenda of the organization that went by that name. It was the 
willingness of the Catholic bishops to speak out 'courageously' on abortion that Jerry 
Falwell cited as the stimulus for his own entry into the political sphere, declares the 
introduction. Pope John Paul II, Jerry Falwell once declared, is the best hope we 
Baptists ever had.<p>
	Askin ominously points out that Phyllis Schlafly... William Bennett... Patrick 
Buchanan... are all Catholics. <p>
	He then goes on to indulge in deconstructing a  newspaper photograph in the 
National Catholic Reporter. Seated on the dais are cardinals John J. O'Connor, 
Bernard Law, Anthony Bevilacqua, James Hickery, and Roger Mahony, whle pounding 
away at the podium before a 'March for Life' audience is a stern faced Jesse Helms...So 
even though the bishops and Helms take opposing positions on virtually every social 
question except reproductive issues, they are political pals.<p>
	Add the pope's anti-Communist crusade to his conservative family agenda, fierce 
opposition to abortion and contraception, lack of recognition of women's rights, an 
authoritarian style of leadership, and one sees a near perfect reflection of the agenda of 
the Religious Right, writes Askin. <p>
	He concludes his introduction with a call for a new crusade against an imposing 
force in public life, with enormous potential to affect politics, public policy, and the 
church. If Weyrich is correct, and this is war, we do well to know the enemy.<p>
  What is surprising is that the board of directors of the Robert Sterling Clark Foundation 
is apparently not ashamed of this document.	
<p>

<a href="#table">Table of Contents</a><p>
<a name="foundation"></a>
<b>Foundation Watch Study</b><p>

A study of recent IRS data has revealed that the median payout rate for grantmaking 
foundations in 1992 was 8.17 percent, up from 7 percent in 1990 as reported in 
Foundation News (March-April, 1994), which used a different method.<p>

  The new analysis, conducted for Foundation Watch, was based on the just-released 
Private Foundations and Charitable Trusts, 1992, in the IRS Statistic of Income Bulletin, 
vol. 15, no. 3.<p>

  The breakdown was as follows:<br><p>

Size of Foundation Average Distributions<br>
<pre>
$100k to $1m		19.7%<br>
$1m to $10m		10.7%<br>
$10m to $25m		10.5%<br>
$25m to $50m		9.1%<br>
$50m to $100m		7.7%<br>
$100m and above		6.4%<br>
</pre>
<p>
  The median payout rate was computed by dividing the median of overall qualifying 
distributions of grantmaking foundations by the median of overall foundation net worth.  
The  average distribution for each foundation size category was determined by dividing 
the net worth on column 46 of the "Private Foundation" spread sheet of the  IRS Statistic 
of Income Bulletin by the qualifying distributions in column 52 of the same document for 
each category.<p>


