<P>
<b><i>January 1997</i></b>
<p>
<ul><li><FONT COLOR="#800000"><a href="#1">To Forgive and Reconcile </a>by Susan Olasky. 
<br><I> Every January pro-life supporters observe Sanctity 
of Life Sunday in observance of the Supreme Court's 
</I><b>Roe v. Wade</b><I> decision in 1973.  In this month's 
</I><b>PCS</b>, Susan Olasky <i> highlights the efforts of groups attempting 
to help women cope with the pain of post-abortion 
trauma while facing their act honestly and seeking God's 
forgiveness.</i>
<li><a href="#2"> More information on post-abortion stress and counseling.</a>
<li><a href="#3"> <i>"He Might Have Been There..."</i></a> by Marvin Olasky
<li> Frederica Matthewes-Green<i> writes of her 
experience with &quot;Common Ground,&quot; an organization seeking 
areas of agreement, not compromise, between pro-life 
and pro-choice forces.</I>
<br>In: <a href="#4">Pro-life, Pro-choice: <I>Can We Talk?</i></a> by Frederica Matthewes-Green.</font>
</ul>
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<a name="1"><center><b>
<h2><i><U>To Forgive and Reconcile</U></h2>
<FONT SIZE="+1">Helping Women through their Grief</FONT></i></center>
<p>
By Susan Olasky</b>
<p>
<P><I><blockquote>Karen was 15 when she became pregnant.  Her 
parents urged her to have an abortion -- they didn't want to 
raise another child, they said.  And since she was already in 
her eleventh week, there was no time to wait.  Her mother took 
her to the clinic and the thing was done.  Crisis over.</blockquote></I>
<P>
<dd>
Or so it seemed.  But that abortion would haunt Karen 
for years until she went through a post-abortion support 
group sponsored by a crisis pregnancy center.
<P>
<dd>
Karen is like many others -- Catholic and evangelical, 
Christian and atheist, pro-life and pro-choice -- who have 
sought help to deal with past abortions.  Although officially there is 
no such thing as post abortion stress, the experience of tens 
of thousands of women and men suggests that abortion has 
spiritual, social, and psychological consequences that 
professional therapists are only now beginning to acknowledge.
<P><dd>Hurting women haven't waited for  the American 
Psychiatric Association to recognize their pain.  They have developed 
a network of support groups, sympathetic clergy and 
therapists through organizations such as Project Rachel, sponsored by 
the Catholic Church; or PACE, sponsored by Care Net, an 
evangelical network of crisis pregnancy centers.   Other have 
turned to Abortion Survivors Anonymous (ASA), a 12-step 
program, or one of hundreds of other groups with names like 
Silent Voices or Rachel's Hope.  Even some family planning 
clinics now acknowledged the existence of post-abortion distress 
and have begun to offer counseling.
<P><I><blockequote>For five years after her abortion,  Karen devoted herself 
to making a relationship with the father of her never-born baby. 
 &quot;I put all of my focus into validating the relationship I had 
with the boy,&quot; she says.  And even after moving thousands of 
miles away and engaging in relationships with other guys, 
she believed her future was with him: &quot;[the other guys] were to 
pass the time until Scott and I could be together.&quot;</blockquote></I>
<P>
<dd>Most women resume their lives after an abortion.  As 
Lisa Salcedo, former longtime PACE (Post Abortion 
Counseling and Education) coordinator at the Austin Crisis 
Pregnancy Center, notes, the most common emotion immediately 
following an abortion is relief.  &quot;A crisis pregnancy is indeed 
thatit is a crisis.  And when you choose an abortion, that crisis is 
over . . . of  course you're going to feel relief.&quot;
<P>
<dd>But some women find the relief is short-lived. They 
may show mild signs of depression as  Jennifer did.  She was 18 
and a college student when she had her abortion.  It took place 
in August and Jennifer did fine in school that fall semester.  But 
by spring things were different.  &quot;When I'm sad the best thing 
for me is to sleep,&quot; she says.  &quot;I slept that whole spring semester 
in college.&quot; Later on she felt a lack of desire for sex in her 
marriage and a general emotional numbness, feeling neither great 
sorrow nor great joy about anything.
<P>
<dd>Abortion Survivors Anonymous explains the reason 
for depression this way: &quot;When a child dies, grief is a 
normal reaction of surviving family members.  Few of us thought 
of abortion as a death loss.  We did not expect or 
acknowledge grief.  So we stuffed our feelings of emptiness, loss, anger 
and despair.  Normal grief in time leads to reconciliation 
and acceptance of life without the one we lost.  When grief 
goes unrecognized or denied, it goes undercover and endangers 
our physical, mental, emotional and spiritual well being.&quot;
<P>Vicki Thorn, executive director of the National Office 
of Post-Abortion Reconciliation &amp; Healing and founder of 
the Catholic Church's Project Rachel, puts it this way: &quot;The 
societal message says that this experience solves a problem and 
that it is a non-experience.&quot;
<P>For some women the abortion aftermath goes much 
further than mild feelings of sadness or depression.  Lorraine 
dabbled in drugs and alcohol and suffered through bouts of 
depression after her abortion.  She was able to hold herself together 
during her father's last illness and death, but then she began a 
period of self-loathing.  &quot;I put myself in a position where I could 
get really, really hurt -- physically hurt, emotionally hurt, on 
purpose, because I hated myself so badly that I wanted 
somebody -- although I couldn't do it myself -- I would wish my 
car would break down out in the middle of nowhere and wish 
that someone would pull over and actually physically abuse me 
and rape me and leave me for dead.  I can't tell you how many 
times I felt that.&quot; 
<P>As Abortion Survivors Anonymous explains, &quot;'Time 
doesn't heal all wounds' . . . .  When abortion wounds our hearts, 
tears may cleanse it and our pain may be soothed in sharing 
with others.  But when we hide our tears and seal our grief in 
tight-lipped isolation, time only makes it worse.&quot;
<P>Both Jennifer and Lorraine showed symptoms typical of 
post abortion syndrome (PAS), although Jennifer's symptoms 
were mild.  Vicki Thorn has put together a list of manifestations 
of what she calls &quot;abortion's aftermath.&quot;  
<P>It includes low self-esteem, grief, depression, guilt, a 
sense of alienation from self, family, and friends, shame, 
isolation, anger, dreams, flashbacks, ideas of suicide, drug and 
alcohol abuse, and relationship problems.  The intensity and number 
of symptoms differs from one woman to the next.  But even 
when the feelings are very intense, women rarely make the 
association between their feelings and behavior and an 
abortion because they have successfully absorbed the message 
that abortion solves problems, and does not create them.  It 
usually takes a trigger event for a woman to make the connection.  
<P>
<bolckquote><I>Five years after her abortion, Karen's relationship with 
the baby's father, which she had nurtured as a way to justify 
the abortion, was over.  She slipped into depression.  &quot;That's 
when I started doing drugs and got heavily involved in one 
night stands.  I became worthless.  I sought avenues to try to cover 
up how I was feeling and the worthlessness that I felt.  I sought 
out really toxic relationshipslike each relationship got 
even worse and worse. I kept putting myself into 
circumstances where  I think I wanted to be killed, but not having 
enough courage to do it myself. . . .  I think deep down I really 
wanted to get rid of the feeling I was having and I didn't know what 
to do with it.  Didn't really know how to pinpoint it either, until 
I came face to face with death, really, because my boyfriend 
had killed himself while he was talking to me on the phone. . . . 
 That's when I realized, &quot;Whoa, why am I choosing death?&quot;
<P>Four years ago Karen gave birth to a daughter.  And 
though she says she had grieved over the abortion in lots of ways, 
her daughter's birth triggered something new.  &quot;I started 
grieving for the baby.  That's when I had guilt.  It was a panicky 
feeling because  I wanted to go to the clinic, which was 2,500 
miles away, and find my baby.  There was just a real feeling of loss 
and mourning and not having anywhere to go to try to fix it.&quot;</I></blockquote>
<P>
<dd>For Karen, the birth of a baby triggered her 
long-suppressed memories of a previous abortion.  Sometimes an 
abortion protest or a movie about fetal development, or even a 
popular television movie can act as a trigger.  Vicki Thorn said 
the recent HBO movie, &quot;If These Walls Could Talk,&quot; resulted 
in phone calls to her office.  Sometimes the trigger is as 
ordinary as seeing a child the same age as the aborted one would be.  
<P>
<dd>For an older woman who has never married or is 
having fertility problems, the trigger may be feeling that she  
aborted the only child she may ever have. Ava Torre-Bueno, a 
therapist in San Diego, and for 10 years involved in abortion 
counseling at a Planned Parenthood clinic, still supports abortion rights.  But she 
sees many women in her practice who are suffering from what she calls &quot;post 
abortion distress.&quot;  
<P>
<dd>Ms. Torre-Bueno says an abortion that made sense during one period in 
a woman's life takes on a different meaning when her circumstances change. 
 She may, for instance, be in her 40s now, and having hot flashes at night. 
 Never married with no current partner, she begins to view an abortion she had at 28 &quot;as her only 
chance to have a child.&quot;  According to Ms. Torre-Bueno, &quot;her 
feelings change with the new circumstances.&quot;  Or there may be 
an intervening medical event.  &quot;A partner may die, now 
the abortion is a mistake, before it wasn't.&quot;
<P>
<dd>The triggering event, whatever it is, may happen two 
years, five years, ten years or longer after the abortion.  Lisa 
Salcedo, the Austin PACE coordinator, says lots of women feel 
some pain regarding the loss of their babies.  &quot;It typically shows 
up when they hit their  late 20s,  30s  and early 40s -- when they 
are most likely to have children of their own.&quot;  Women 
who managed to grieve the loss of their baby at the time of 
the abortion are less likely to have dramatic symptoms later on, 
but Ms. Salcedo is emphatic that at some point all abortive 
women will mourn: &quot;You can't lose a child and not grieve 
sometime,&quot; she says.  &quot;You must mourn for that baby. . . .  That's just 
the way we're created.&quot;
<P>
<P><CENTER><B><H4>Project Rachel</H4></B>
</CENTER><P>
<dd>When the crisis comes, women have several choices of where to go and what 
to do for help.  Many Catholic women have found healing with Project Rachel.  It 
was founded in 1984 by Vicki Thorn, who at that time was the Respect Life 
coordinator for the diocese of Milwaukee.  She saw the need for 
the Catholic Church to be reaching out to women who had 
experienced abortions, especially as she saw a friend struggle 
with post abortion pain.  &quot;I can live with my adoption, but not 
with my abortion,&quot; this friend told her.  Ms. Thorn believed &quot;that 
we as the Church needed to be responding since the pain is 
so incredible.&quot;
<P>
<dd>In September of 1984, Project Rachel was born as a 
national model of post-abortion counseling.  From the beginning 
Project Rachel relied on professional counselors and clergy 
because &quot;we needed to offer the best we had.&quot;  Project Rachel 
continues to rely primarily on professionals, although some dioceses 
have started support groups.  Thousands of people in the 
church structure have been trained over the past 12 years; in one 
year alone, 3,000 people received training.
<P>
<dd>In Austin, Project Rachel has seen 200 to 300 women in 
the five years it has been operating.  The group is a 
low-budget operation, having just enough money to pay for a phone line 
in volunteer coordinator Susan Stavinoha's house and a 
brochure, which is made available in area Catholic churches. Like 
Project Rachel nationally, the local affiliate uses clergy and 
professional counselors, although two years ago it began a 
support group.  So far 18 women have gone through it.
<P>
<dd>Ms.  Stavinoha says several things happen in a Project 
Rachel group.  First a woman &quot; needs to tell her story in detail.  We 
go in detail in what you wore, who went with you, what did it 
smell like.  They need to get in touch with anger, disgust, 
hatred towards their selves, their spouse, the father of the child, 
their parents, the Church.&quot; 
<P>
<dd>Second, the group works &quot;on establishing some 
relationship between the mother and the child.  Once they acknowledge 
that `yes, it was their child and they had a hand in destroying the 
life of that child,' they can begin grieving.&quot;
<P>
<dd>The third step is forgiveness: God forgiving them, and 
the women forgiving themselves.  Ms. Stavinoha says, &quot;They 
think that God will never forgive them and they will go to hell. 
 They're really at the bottom and when they see that God is 
there for them, that relationship becomes stronger.&quot;
<P>
<dd>Project Rachel is designed to use the sacraments and 
traditions of the Catholic Church to bring about reconciliation. 
 Whether a woman chooses to see a priest, a therapist or take 
part in a support group is up to her.  &quot;Within the Catholic 
tradition of reconciliation, its important that at some point they go to 
a priest.&quot;
<P>
<dd>One of the most intriguing innovations in Austin's 
Project Rachel has been the introduction of art projects by art 
therapist Stephanie Woodruff.  The purpose of the art is not to make 
a product, but to open up an experience to a woman.  
For example, participants use craft clay in one project to 
sculpt some aspect of the life that was lost during an abortion.  
Ms. Woodruff says that the models that result are &quot;healing 
images that define for the woman that this is a life.  That it is a life 
that is specifically related to her.  That she is the mother.&quot;
<P>
<dd>An icebreaker used often during the first session has 
the leader asking participants to draw the answer to the 
question: &quot;If you were a flower, what would you look like?&quot;  
Afterwards each woman describes her flower and explains its meaning 
to the group.  A third project uses white and black materials 
to depict the abortion experience itself.  The works often 
express all the anger involved in an abortion.
<P>
<dd>Throughout the sessions, participants use the art projects 
to stimulate thoughts and deeply buried feelings and then 
explain them to the group.
<P>
<P><CENTER><B><H4>Post Abortion Counseling and Education (PACE)</H4></B>
</CENTER><P>
<dd>PACE is the largest post abortion network in the country. 
 Currently, PACE programs for women are offered by 297 
crisis pregnancy centers in the U.S.  that are affiliated with Care 
Net. Forty-four centers offer men's groups as well.  In 1986, 
when the program started, 700 PACE Bible studies were distributed. 
 Between 40,000 and 50,000 have been sold in the past ten years.
<P>
<dd>Although there are many similarities between Project 
Rachel and PACE, there is one basic difference.  PACE is a 
Bible Study.  According to Judy Brown McDonough, Care 
Net's general counsel, &quot;PACE is all about who God is.  It's 
the character of God and who he is that promotes healing.&quot;  
Most of the women who come to a PACE Bible study are 
Christian women.  According to Ms. Salcedo, &quot;Especially for 
Christian women there are  guilt and forgiveness issues.  Not only the 
guilt and forgiveness from God issues, but also the forgiveness 
of oneself.  You have to get to the other side, where you are 
willing to forgive yourself and move on.&quot;
<P>
<dd>But shame and guilt can make it hard for Christian women 
to come forward.  Jennifer, who had become a Christian 
several years after her abortion, never told anyone in her church 
about it.  On Sanctity of Human Life Sunday (in January) &quot;a 
well respected man gave his abortion testimony,&quot; she says.  
&quot;The way the congregation was accepting of him, supportive of 
him and sincerely thankful that he had had the courage to 
share -- when I saw him stand up, and then their reaction, it gave 
me inspiration to go to talk to someone.&quot;
<P>
<dd>Ms. Salcedo acknowledges the problem in many 
evangelical churches.   &quot;There are so many cases of women being 
rejected in our churches, that make women and men so wary, 
so frightened to share it with people. . . .  A woman who has 
had an abortion feels bad enough about it.  She doesn't need 
any more criticism or judgment, and she certainly doesn't need 
to be reminded how much of a sin it was.  Particularly 
Christian women know it was a sin -- most of them.  They need 
outstretched hands, a shoulder, a friendly ear to listen, to help 
them through their healing path.&quot;  According to Ms. Salcedo, 
that's what PACE offers.
<P>
<dd>Most PACE groups are led by volunteers who have 
had abortions themselves.  Typically, a group of five to 
eight women will go through the PACE study, looking up the 
Bible passages at home,  and discussing issues of anger, 
grief, depression,  and forgiveness when they are all together. 
<P>
<dd>Lorraine, the woman who had wished to be raped and left 
for dead, said the most important thing she gained from her 
eight week PACE group was an idea of &quot;God's grace for you.  
When you feel so awful for what you've done. . . .  And then 
He actually shows you the Scripture . . . that He has those 
loving arms and when you walk to him, He's there.&quot;
<P>
<dd>Not every person comes out of a PACE group with a 
huge revelation -- nor are they all seeking one.  Jennifer 
wanted &quot;people to know me with all my faults and PACE gave me 
the courage to say, `I made a huge mistake'. . . .  I am so 
thankful that God allowed me to go through PACE and go through 
the abortion because before the abortion I thought I was  a 
good person that would go to heaven, and now I know just 
how deceitful and manipulative and self-centered and selfish I 
was apart from God.  And I know I am not any worse than anyone else, even 
those who haven't had abortions.&quot;
<P>
<dd>Getting to that place, though, is not easy.  During one week of a 
PACE group, each participant writes a letter to God expressing her anger with 
everyone and everything connected to the abortion.  The letters are not 
pretty because they vent so much anger.  For many women it's hard even to 
acknowledge that the anger exists because they've been holding the lid on it for so many years.  But 
once encouraged to express it, it comes pouring out.  It may 
be directed against the boyfriend or husband who encouraged 
the abortion.  Sometimes parents are the targets, or siblings, or 
the abortionistand always there is anger directed by the 
woman at herself.  
<P>
<dd>Participants aren't encouraged to nurse their anger.  The 
next week they read scripture passages about forgiveness and 
their duty to forgive those who have hurt them.  While not 
every woman can move from anger to forgiveness in a week, 
the process is an important one -- whether it takes a week, a 
month, or a year -- because carrying around a load of bitterness 
is harmful to her.  
<P>
<dd>Even though PACE has grown tremendously over the 
past ten years, Care Net's Judy McDonough is not satisfied.  
&quot;We should have PACE groups in the millions,&quot; she says.  About 
2.7 million born-again women have had abortions, and we've 
only sold in the tens of thousands [of Bible Studies].&quot;
<P>
<CENTER><P><B><H4>Abortion Survivors Anonymous (ASA)</H4></B>
</CENTER><P>
<dd>ASA is a 12-step program based on the twelve steps 
of Alcoholics Anonymous.  The group, which was founded in 
San Diego, California in 1988, operates on a shoe string since 
it receives no funding from anyone accept participants.  
The group also stays clear from all political controversies.  Sarah 
J. said, &quot;We stay completely apart from whatever controversy 
is going on in this country.  We all have our own 
individual opinions. . . .  Our premise is, when someone calls and says, 
`I'm pro-choice, anti-religious, can you help?' We say `It 
doesn't make any difference what your standing is.  You hurt.  
Your emotions have no opinions.&quot;
<P>Since the group's founding in 1988, it has received calls 
from 37 states and average about a call a day.  ASA has sent 
out several hundred workbooks during that time. The work 
book can be used by individuals, but it also contains information 
on how to run a small group; it states clearly that &quot;the study is 
most effective in a small group setting.&quot;
<P>
<dd>Perhaps the greatest difference in the 12 Step approach 
to healing is spiritual. PACE is unabashedly evangelical 
Protestant in its understanding of God and the Bible.  Project 
Rachel is a ministry of the Catholic Church.  But ASA follows the 
lead of AA and teaches the need to believe that an unnamed 
&quot;Power greater than ourselves can restore us to wholeness.&quot; 
According to Sarah J., ASA's founders felt there was 
an empty holea space that needed filling for those women 
from no particular theological tradition who needed help.
<P>ASA explains its philosophy to newcomers: &quot;Our goal 
for our journey to wholeness after abortion is three fold:  first, 
to work through our feelings of fear, anger, grief and guilt. 
 Second,  to reconcile with others who shared responsibility 
for the abortion, with God, with the aborted child(ren), and 
with ourselves.  And third, to sort guilt from grief and begin 
healthy grieving for our children.
<P>
<CENTER><P><B><H4>Peace After Abortion</H4></B>
</CENTER><P>For a long time it has been pro-life people who have 
fought to have PAS recognized as a legitimate mental health diagnosis. 
 Most pro-choice advocates have denied its existence.  But 
Ava Torre-Bueno is different.  This licensed M.S.W. began 
doing pregnancy counseling in a Planned Parenthood Clinic in 
1975, two years after <I>Roe v. Wade</I> was decided.  Five years later 
she became director of counseling at that clinic.   She left the 
clinic in 1985 and three years later opened up a private 
counseling practice.  Ms.  Torre-Bueno continues to see women who 
are distressed by their previous abortions.
<P>
<dd>Although she denies the existence of PAS, preferring to 
talk about post abortion distress, Ms. Torre-Bueno does 
acknowledge that abortion affects women.  She has written a book on 
the subject called <I>Peace after Abortion</I>.  In her opinion the 
abortion experience cracks open old feelings that have been locked 
up inside a woman.  She says that anxiety about abortion 
&quot;has opened up long suppressed feelings that they're bad, 
they're wrong. . . .  Something unresolved has come back on them.&quot;
<P>
<dd>So in her counseling practice she does not focus on 
grieving the loss of a baby, as the other programs do.  She encourages 
her clients to think about when else they have had similar feelings. 
 Maybe they are deeper, older issues of abandonment 
coming from the death or divorce of parents, and then Ms. 
Torre-Bueno encourages her clients to deal with those issues.
<P>
<dd>Post abortion distress, she says,  can be beneficial.  
Clients learn that &quot;you can heal spiritually, you can heal 
emotionally, you can grow up. . . .  It's like the silver lining.  You can 
heal old stuff.  You're in pain from it, but you can heal from it.&quot;
<P>
<dd>Although Ms. Torre-Bueno has received some positive 
feedback from family planning clinics, especially in the 
Pacific Northwest, she has also heard the question, `Why don't 
you stop talking about it?' from many of her pro-choice colleagues. 
 For a long time, she says, &quot;pro-choice folks have said no.  
They wouldn't look at [post abortion distress] seriously and deeply. 
 They wouldn't address it.&quot;
<P>
<dd>The publication of Naomi Wolf's essay, &quot;Our Bodies, 
Our Souls&quot; in <I>The New Republic</I> several years ago was a 
turning point of sorts: &quot;I was so glad that she had opened up the 
issue to the public. . . .  I'm getting orders [for the book] from 
family planning clinics.  Some think it's great, others won't order it.&quot; 
<P>
<dd>To her critics who think she has been co-opted by 
pro-life people, Ms. Torre-Bueno responds: &quot;They can't hear the 
client.&quot;  She explains that many women come into family 
planning clinics saying, &quot;I want the pill because I could never 
have another abortion.&quot;  The family planning counselors are 
so pleased to have a woman who is committed to using 
birth control that they don't hear what the client is really saying.  
Ms. Torre-Bueno says counselors should say, &quot;Tell me about 
your previous abortion,&quot; but they don't because &quot;people in 
family planning don't want to hear that she had a problem.&quot;   Her 
goal, says Ms. Torre-Bueno, &quot;is to just get them to hear that 
sentence and ask the next sentence correctly.&quot;
<P>
<CENTER><P><H4><B>Dads For Life</B></H4>
</CENTER><P>
<dd>Although most post abortion groups target women, there 
is a growing recognition that men, grandparents and siblings can 
 all have strong feelings about abortion.
<P>
<dd>Gary Bell was married and working in a TV repair shop 
in West Virginia when his wife had an abortion.  It took him 
seven years before he ever talked about it to anyone, even her.  
But then she had an affair and wanted a divorce.  &quot;
We had a 16-month old son. . . .  I lost everything that mattered to me, my 
wife and my son.&quot;
<P>
<dd>A local TV program, featuring NOW's Molly Yard 
talking about how fathers can't be good single parents, 
triggered something in Mr. Bell. He called the television studio.  
The producer was intrigued by his story -- and the idea that 
abortion affects men -- and scheduled him as a guest.  Men began 
coming out of the woodwork, he says, interested in getting help 
for themselves.  National television programs, including 
<I>Nightline</I>, scheduled him as a guest and 
<I>Newsweek</I> featured him in an article.
<P>
<dd>The attitude of the national media, he says, was &quot;very 
biased towards the women's point of view.  They were upset with 
the idea that men would have the right to stop an abortion.&quot;
<P>
<dd>Mr. Bell set up an organization called Dads for Life, 
and began receiving calls and letters from men suffering 
from abortion's aftermath.  Men, he says, go through many of 
the same abortion related feelings as women.  And social status 
is no predictor:  Mr. Bell has talked to people &quot;from all walks 
of life, from street bums to the wealthiest man you can imagine. 
 They all have the same kinds of feelings.&quot;
<P>
<dd>But there are differences: The man may have been the one 
to force his girlfriend or wife to have the abortion; he may 
have opposed it and been powerless to stop it;  or perhaps he 
didn't even know she was pregnant.  Many men wanted to be dads, Mr. Bell says,  
&quot;They may say, `I want to live up to my 
responsibilities' and the lady says `no you can't.'&quot;  
<P>
<dd>It has been harder for men to admit post- abortion pain.  As Mr. Bell puts 
it, &quot;People look at you funny if you say, 
`I'm hurting because my wife had an abortion.'  It's a lonely feeling because we 
are conditioned to think it is so private.  I've heard, `take it like 
a man.'  Well, how do you do that?&quot;
<P>
<dd>That's what happened to Ken, a young man who 
went through ASA's support group.  Though he tried to talk his 
girl friend out of an abortion, she went ahead with it.  Later he 
wrote, &quot;Elisha can't understand when I tell her how much I hurt.  
I know I wasn't the one who actually had the abortion, but I 
lost my son too.&quot;
<P>Vicki Thorn says that the National Office of Post 
Abortion Reconciliation and Healing receives far more calls from 
men than we ever used to.&quot;  It's similar to the situation for 
women ten years ago, she says.  After a speaking engagement men 
will come, &quot;one-by-one with tears in their eyes to talk to me.&quot;  
Ms. Thorn says that the growth of Promise Keepers and 
Covenant Keepers &quot;is going to unleash a tidal wave of pain among men.&quot; 
<P>
<dd>If that is true, local support groups are going to be 
overwhelmed.  Many local PACE and Project Rachel groups do 
not currently have support groups for men, and Mr. Bell has 
found it difficult to run and fund Dads for Life himself.  He has 
looked for a national group to provide leadership in this area, but 
has not been successful.
<P>
<CENTER><H4><B>National Office of Post Abortion Reconciliation and Healing (NOPARH)</B></H4></CENTER>
<P>
<dd>NOPARH is central clearinghouse for information 
about post abortion stress.  Although Vicki Thorn was the founder 
of the Catholic Church's Project Rachel, NOPARH is 
non-sectarian and has a broad outreach.  It keeps track of post 
abortion support groups throughout the country, and at its yearly 
convention at Marquette University, NOPARH tries to keep 
volunteers, therapists, clergy, and post-abortive women and 
men informed about the latest research on the issue.
<P>
<dd>Ms. Thorn  sees at least three main  challenges for the future. 
 First, she is concerned that there are &quot;no healing outreaches 
in the black community.&quot;  She believes that post abortion 
aftermath can explain some of the troubles in the black family.  
&quot;It has to have an impact on family systems,&quot; she says.  &quot;There 
isn't anything else in the country that has that scope.&quot;  And she 
says the problem will not be solved until leadership from the 
black community comes forward. 
<P>
<dd>Second, she is concerned about the potential implications 
of RU-486 as an easily accessible alternative form of abortion. 
 Ms. Thorn says RU-486 will &quot;create immediate and 
acute trauma.  We're going to have women having acute reactions.&quot;
<P>
<dd>The problem with the chemical is that it is 
self-administered, thus perhaps compounding feelings of guilt,  and it 
requires several days to bring about the abortion.  Even Ava 
Torre-Bueno says, &quot;I can't imagine doing RU-486.  The dragging 
out of this thing seems so awful to me.&quot;  
<P>
<dd>If a woman were to change her mind after taking the 
required first drug, but before taking the second one necessary 
to complete the abortion, &quot;that's going to be hell,&quot; Ms. 
Torre-Bueno says.  And Ms. Thorn adds that a woman's home, 
where the abortion takes place, is likely to become an aversive 
place to her, just as an abortion clinic is aversive to many women 
after their abortions.
<P>
<dd>It is too soon to tell what the consequences of RU-486 will 
be; clinical trials have just ended and the drug is not yet 
widely available.  But post abortion experts expect it to have 
serious effects on the women they see who are trying to piece back a 
life after abortion.
<P>
<dd>The third area of concern is lack of funding for research 
into post-abortion stress.  Ms. Thorn says that &quot;pro-abortion 
people are pumping money into politicized research&quot; designed to 
show that abortion does not cause problems.  Many of the 
studies funded by these people track women for only six months 
after an abortion, long before any adverse side effects 
generally show up.  As long as the &quot;secular community doesn't want 
to believe PAS exists,&quot; Ms. Thorn says, there won't be funding 
for it.
<P>
<dd>Debates about whether post abortion stress is actually a 
form of post traumatic stress syndrome don't seem to matter all 
that much to the volunteers in the field.  Many have had 
abortions of their own.  As Project Rachel's Susan Stavinoha says, 
 &quot;People can not deny a woman who has had an abortion 
and speaks from her heart about the effects of it.  It's not a statistic. 
 It's a true story.  If enough women tell their true stories, it 
will change things little by little.&quot;
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<a name="2">
<P>
