<p>
<a name="3">
<CENTER><H4><B><I>&quot;He Might Have Been There...&quot;</B></I><BR></H4>
</CENTER><p>
by Marvin Olasky
<p>
<dd>Post abortion grief is not a new phenomenon.  One hundred and fifty years ago,  America went through 
another &quot;free love period&quot;; one hundred and twenty years 
ago, Elizabeth Evans wrote a book, <I>The Abuse of 
Maternity</I>, in which she described the effects of abortion on women.  
One told Evans, &quot;I recognized my real condition as a 
criminal, none the less because undetected and unpunished.  
[The memory] serves as an effectual damper upon 
whatever degree of pride or satisfaction I might otherwise feel in 
the more praiseworthy deeds of my career.&quot; 
<P>
<dd>A second told Evans, &quot;From the moment when I 
began to appreciate my irreparable loss, my thoughts were 
filled with imaginings as to what might have been the worth 
of that child's individuality . . . nor, during the interval, 
have I ever read of an accident by land or by water, or of a 
critical moment in a battle, or of a good cause lost through lack 
of a brave defender, but my heart has whispered, `He 
might have been there to help and save; he might have been 
able to lead that forlorn hope; his word or his deed might 
have brought that wise plan to successful issue.'&quot; 
<P>
<dd>Post abortion grief caused another to say, &quot;I was for 
a long time as near being insane as one can be without 
really going mad. . . .  I had an idea that I had lost, through 
that unnatural deed, the normal powers and qualities of a 
human being.  I no longer ate and drank with the old hunger 
and thirst, nor slept the quiet sleep of innocence; I took no 
heed of the passage of time, and all that I saw and heard 
seemed to be the occurrences of a dream, as though life was 
already finished for me.&quot; 
<P>
<dd>The sorrow at not having a grave or place in which 
to mourn the child led another mother to say, &quot;I envy a 
mother who goes to weep beside her baby's grave; because 
she knows where it is laid, and remembers how it looked in 
life, and is not ashamed to say, `I have lost a child.'  And 
when I hear mothers lamenting over such a loss, I pity 
them indeed; but I feel like saying to them, `You think you 
are deeply afflicted, but your trouble is really light, because 
it is not mingled with remorse, and you are not to blame 
for the infant's death.'  Truly, all sorrow that I have ever 
known or heard of is not to be compared with my sorrow, and 
that or others who have sinned in like manner!&quot;  
<br>--
<I>Cited in </I>Abortion Rites: A Social History of Abortion in 
America.
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<a name="4">
<CENTER><H4><B>Pro-life, Pro-choice: <I>Can We Talk?</I></h4></CENTER>
<P>
By Frederica Matthewes-Green</B><p>
<dd>&quot;What's the point of talking to pro-choicers?&quot; a 
pro-lifer may well ask. Yet in cities across the country 
some pro-lifers have decided to do exactly that. 
Pro-life/pro-choice dialogue meetingsa phenomenon known 
as &quot;Common Ground&quot;have sprung up spontaneously 
in cities from San Francisco to St. Louis to Buffalo.
<P>
<dd>The motivation for, and the style of, these 
meetings varies a great deal. What they have in common is 
some basic ground rulesto speak respectfully, avoid 
combative argument, and keep group discussion 
confidential. They also share goals that are fairly modest. 
While the term &quot;common ground&quot; may, in some contexts, 
imply compromise, that is not the case here. Abortion 
dialogue groups do not try to negotiate a set of statements 
about abortion that are agreeable to all sidesfor 
example, pro-lifers giving up early abortions while 
pro-choicers give up late ones. Instead, dialogue participants look 
for areas where agreement already exists (adoption, 
for example) and try to build upon it.
<P>
<dd>Three possible benefits can result from such 
discussion. First, the two sides may actually find 
concrete action they can agree on, action that hopefully 
will reduce the numbers of abortions even while it 
continues to remain legal. Second, civil dialogue sets an 
attractive example for the &quot;muddled middle,&quot; who are 
disturbed and wearied by the polarized debate. This 
stimulates renewed hope, honest discussion of ambivalence, 
and fresh thinking. Third, dialogue, in itself,  has a 
goodness. As a Christian, I know that I am called to love 
my enemies. Before I became a pro-life activist, I didn't 
even have any enemies! But now, since I &quot;cannot love 
the brother I have not seen,&quot; I make an effort to attend 
our local common ground group regularly. As trust 
has grown over the years, so has love.  In our common 
ground group I can speak my mind freely, and know that my 
pro-choice friends will listen and understand, even when 
they disagree. I lose nothing by doing the same for them.
<P>
<dd>As local groups proliferate, the national 
umbrella linking them, the Network for Life and Choice, 
finds itself increasingly busy. The Network, a project of 
the Washington, DC-based Search for Common Ground, 
grew from a request from one such local group. In 
the wake of an Operation Rescue campaign, clergy in 
Buffalo, NY, asked for help in enabling opponents to 
understand each other. Search for Common Ground had 
facilitated dialogues between Israelis and Arabs and 
between Americans and Russians, but this would be their 
first purely domestic project.
<P>
<dd>Four years later, the Network has accomplished 
some important goals, and has set more for the future. 
Committees composed of both pro-life and pro-choice 
members have released working papers on adoption and 
teen pregnancy, and the movement's first national 
conference was held this past June in Madison, Wisconsin. At 
a recent meeting of the Network's national steering 
committee (which balances members from each side), 
Network director Mary Jacksteit listed ongoing and 
potential projects:
<P> 
<dd>The Network's Task Force on Adoption has met 
with leaders of several adoption education groups, and 
is seeking ways to counter negative publicity about 
that option with accurate information. The Task Force 
intends to develop an educational program for direct 
service providers, media messages and programs, and 
an educational program for adolescents and their families.
<P> 
<dd>The Action Initiative Pilot Program on Teen 
Pregnancy was conducted in Buffalo, NY. Nearly a year 
of preparation went into a two-day forum involving 
fifty adults and ten teens, who generated a list of seven 
areas of common ground. The next phase of this project 
will examine how to move forward in action on these items.
<P> 
<dd>A new working paper will be developed between 
an Operation Rescue activist and an abortion clinic 
administrator. Topic: abortion clinic demonstrations.
<P> 
<dd>A team will explore the feasibility of creating a 
data bank of facts about abortion that neither side 
disputes, and possibly a glossary as well. This would be an 
&quot;unbiased source&quot; available to the press and public. 
Some conflicts regarding details of the abortion issue are 
not based in philosophical disagreement, but only 
uncertainty about facts, and the Network may be able to 
defuse some unnecessary conflict this way.
<p>
<hr>
<p>
